<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Radicals     03-25 0891</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Radicals,0919</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radicalism a Generation Later: Smothered by Affluence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Saturday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They led snake-dancing students in huge protests 20
years ago, but today Japan's radical leftists encounter the blank
stare of indifference in a land blessed with affluence greater than
anyone had dreamed.
   Although they got headlines with threatening to disrupt the
summer Olympics in Seoul and Emperor Hirohito's funeral, the
radicals clearly have lost the widespread support of those days
when student unrest swept campuses around the world.
   A former radical looked back on the zeal of his college days
with fondness, but said they are gone for good. The former member
of the Kakurokyo, or Revolutionary Workers Association, now is a
photographer for a conservative weekly news magazine.
   ``When we were college students, Marxism was a fad,'' he said,
asking that his name not be used. ``Students these days don't have
any philosophy.''
   He said affluence was the main reason radicalism has lost its
appeal, but revulsion over the bloody acts of ultra-left groups
also keeps their ranks small.
   Even housewives and businessmen sympathized with some protests a
generation ago, but the radical left sent itself into rapid decline
with events in 1972 that shocked the nation: the Japanese Red Army
attack at Israel's Lod Airport that killed 28 people and wounded
dozens, and the United Red Army slaughter of 14 members for alleged
ideological deviations.
   Police actions and internecine violence have left many of the
best-known radical groups defunct, weakened or based outside Japan.
   National police officials still fear the Japanese Red Army, but
say its membership has dwindled to about 20. It is based in Lebanon
and said to be run by Fusako Shigenobu, who once worked in a soy
sauce factory.
   Authorities believe the group is more capable of carrying out
terrorist operations abroad and cite its alleged involvement in an
explosion outside a U.S. military club in Naples last April. It
threatened to disrupt Hirohito's funeral in Feb. 24, but did not do
so.
   Another well-known terrorist group, the Red Army Faction formed
in 1969, is based in North Korea and has virtually no organization
left in Japan.
   Takuji Otsu, the lawyer for an admitted hijacker, said:
``Students today have the same amount of dissatisfaction with the
government, but they have a stronger sense of futility.''
   Otsu's client Yasuhiro Shibata, a 35-year-old member of the Red
Army Faction, is being tried on charges that include forgery,
hostage-taking and grand theft.
   Japan had no laws on hijacking in 1970, when Shibata _ then 16 _
and eight others used samurai swords and a bomb to hijack a Japan
Air Lines flight to North Korea.
   He was arrested last year in Japan after 15 years in Pyongyang,
capital of North Korea, and three years in which his movements are
unclear. His accomplices remain in Pyongyang, and one is believed
to have died.
   Involvement of a high school student in the hijacking stunned a
people already unsettled by demonstrations against the education
system, Vietnam War and a mutual security agreement with the United
States.
   Shibata still supports revolution but said he returned to Japan
to establish an economic and social foundation for a ``new kind of
political movement.''
   His lawyer said in an interview: ``It would be meaningless for
them to profess violence in today's society. I think they have
realized ... that they must do something more in tune with the
times.''
   According to Otsu, his client will not explain what kind of new
movement the radicals plan beyond saying it would ``try to solve
specific problems'' and would not recruit in the colleges.
   Kaoru Tsunoda, a junior at Japan Women's University in Tokyo,
said the leftist movement ``just doesn't have much to do with me. I
think making friends and creating a foundation for my own life is
what's important.''
   Miss Tsunoda said she had begun trying to keep up on politics,
but largely because she thinks it will help her chances for a good
job after graduation.
   A recent survey by the government Management and Coordination
Agency found young Japanese tend to be socially conservative,
apolitical and most interested in ``getting rich.''
   Even in the early 1970s, most abandoned activism after
graduation to avoid rejection by prospective employers.
   The most active radical group, the Chukaku-ha, is a direct
descendant of a faction-ridden movement of college students whose
violent revolt disrupted campuses in March 1969.
   Strikes affected more than half the 377 universities that year
and police arrested 10,000 students. They confiscated 12,000 wooden
staves, 4,000 iron bars and 4,000 firebombs.
   By 1985, arrests of radical leftists had fallen to about 100.
   In a report on 1988, the National Police Agency estimated the
number of radical leftists and anarchists in Japan at about 35,000,
compared with 53,500 in 1969, with the number of activists much
lower.
   Chukaku-ha, or Middle Core Faction, has 3,000-5,000 members, and
several hundred radicals claim allegiance to the Kakurokyo
(Revolutionary Workers Association) and the Senki-ha, or Battle
Flag Faction.
   All three oppose the mainstream Japan Communist Party, which
they say is Stalinist and anti-revolutionary. The party denounces
them as Trotskyite adventurers.
   Dozens of deaths have been reported in factional fights between
the Chukaku-ha and the Kakumaru-ha, or Revolutionary Marxist
Faction, which supports the Communist Party.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
