<DOCNO> AP890325-0006 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-89 0134EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-Sudan Bjt   03-25 0649</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Sudan, Bjt,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Looking For Increased Sudan Relief Effort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. official in charge of foreign
disaster relief is calling on nations around the world to ``put the
cash down'' and help avert a repetition of the massive starvation
that afflicted Sudan last year.
   Julia Taft, director of the State Department's Office of Foreign
Disaster Assistance, said Friday that unless a U.N.-sponsored
emergency relief program succeeds, hundreds of thousands could be
lost.
   The United Nations estimated that more than 250,000 Sudanese
died of starvation last year because food deliveries were impeded
by the civil war between the Sudanese government and the Sudanese
Liberation People's Liberation Army.
   Ms. Taft discussed the U.S. role in Operation Lifeline, the
U.N.-sponsored effort designed to deliver more than 100,000 tons of
food to more than 1 million people next month. Project participants
say it is the largest effort of its kind in a developing nation.
   ``It's a race against time,'' Ms. Taft said, adding that unless
the Sudanese government, the rebels, the United Nations and the
donor nations pull together over the next few weeks ``we will see a
repeat of last year's horror.''
   April has been designated as a ``month of tranquility'' in
Sudan's civil conflict.
   ``Everybody wants peace, but peace will be a hollow victory if
the people for whom peace is the goal are not alive because we
can't deliver the food in time to save them,'' Ms. Taft said.
   The food is to be delivered by train, truck, barge and air to
remote areas in the south before seasonal rains and floods make
transport routes impassable.
   The cost of the U.N. project is $132 million, $55 million of
which still must be raised.
   Ms. Taft said the United States has arranged to provide some $30
million of that amount, and is trying to arrange for an additional
$10 million to pay for a ``food swap'' that would trade some foods
available in Sudan for others that certain segments of the society
need.
   The $30 million is in addition to some $72 million in various
forms of aid the United States has pledged to Sudan since last
February, Ms. Taft said.
   But the United States is concerned, because many nations that
have pledged to help the U.N. relief program with foodstuffs now
need to come forward with cash in order to adapt to the emergency,
month-long relief effort, Ms. Taft said.
   ``We will deliver. But we're quite concerned that the other
donors were not forthcoming. ... For some reason, we're out there
in front and we would like to expand the participation of other
donors in this urgent effort,'' she said. ``We hope the consciences
of these donors will find this opportunity to save lives and put
the cash down.''
   She said she hoped nations such as Japan and Saudi Arabia could
assist the effort. She noted that the Soviet Union was not at a
recent conference in Khartoum on the relief effort ``but they might
well be asked (to contribute). Since their own disaster, they know
the importance of an international effort.''
   She said it was up to the United Nations to formally make such a
request.
   Ms. Taft said she feared that because the crisis had not had the
media coverage of the 1984 famine in Ethiopia, or even the December
Soviet earthquake in Armenia, the international community was not
aware of the severity of the tragedy, even though many nations are
usually more than willing to help.
   ``Some disasters get such broad international coverage, the
whole world feels as though they had come to the aid of mankind,''
Ms. Taft said.
   Ms. Taft, who will be in the region with a congressional
delegation next week, said the traditional donor nations, such as
the British, Dutch, Canadians and Italians, are all being asked to
provide additional funding.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
