<DOCNO> AP890325-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-89 0151EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Cheney     03-25 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cheney,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cheney Says Welch Didn't Speak Officially on MX, Midgetman Plans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air Force Chief of Staff Gen. Larry Welch D.
Welch drew the wrath of Defense Secretary Dick Cheney for
reportedly discussing with members of Congress how to update the
U.S. nuclear deterrent.
   Cheney said Friday that Welch wasn't speaking for the
department, had no right do so and would be rebuked for doing it.
   ``General Welch was free-lancing,'' Cheney told reporters,
saying no decisions on the issue had been reached.
   ``I think it's inappropriate for a uniformed officer to be in a
position where he is, in fact, negotiating an arrangement,'' Cheney
said. ``I will make known to him my displeasure. He was not
speaking for the department.'
   A spokesman for Welch, who is the Air Force's top military
officer, said Welch had no comment.
   Cheney said ``all of our options are open'' when it comes to the
future of the land-based nuclear missile force.
   The Bush administration, like the Reagan administration before
it, is trying to develop a plan for adding a mobile nuclear missile
to America's arsenal.
   The Pentagon has told Congress it would like to buy 50 more of
the 10-warhead MX missiles and place them on rail-car launchers.
Congressional Democrats, however, would prefer to see the
development of a small, single-warhead Midgetman missile that could
be deployed on a truck launcher.
   Welch and Navy Adm. William J. Crowe, the chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, have been searching in recent days for a
compromise.
   According to some members of Congress, Welch has suggested a
compromise in which 50 MX missiles already deployed in silos would
be shifted to rail launchers _ instead of purchasing new missiles _
while the number of Midgetman missiles to be built would be scaled
back from 500 to 300.
   But Cheney said no decision had been made.
   ``To say that a compromise is near, I think, would be
premature,'' Cheney said.
   Cheney declined to discuss cutting the Pentagon's budget, as
President Bush has instructed, saying he needed more time to review
programs.
   He did say that as a general priority he would rather reduce the
size of the armed forces instead of returning to the days of a
``hollow'' military without adequate ammunition or spare parts.
   In another development Friday, acting Air Force Secretary James
F. McGovern said he will step down later this spring to seek a job
in the private sector.
   McGovern has served as the undersecretary, or No. 2, man, in the
Air Force's hierarchy since November 1986 and as the acting
secretary since last December.
   An associate of former Sen. John Tower, McGovern had been widely
expected to take on the Air Force post on a permanent basis had
Tower been confirmed as the secretary of defense.
   Tower's nomination was rejected two weeks ago by the Senate and
President Bush replaced him with Cheney.
   ``In a meeting I had with Defense Secretary Cheney earlier this
week, I indicated that I was inclined to return to the private
sector so that I could finally give my two daughters the attention
they deserve and to pursue several other professional interests,''
McGovern said in a prepared statement.
   An aide said McGovern is planning to leave in May. The aide, who
asked not to be named, insisted that the controversy involving
Welch had played no role in McGovern's decision.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
