<FIRST>r a PM-ChimneySneak     03-25 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chimney Sneak,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Rescue Stuck Burglar From Chimney</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police had to climb a roof and shout
down a chimney to read a burglary suspect his rights after the man
got stuck while allegedly trying to enter a doctor's office.
   James Edward Burgess, 31, was out of the chimney and in jail
Friday on a commercial burglary charge.
   ``I thought it was comical that someone could be so stupid,''
said Dr. George Foster who was awakened at home to let police into
his office.
   Rescuers said they used a truck and rope to hoist Burgess to
safety Thursday.
   ``There were three or four fire trucks out here, the cherry
picker _ it looked like the Florida state fair,'' said Foster.
   ``All I could see were his feet dangling,'' added the
44-year-old gynecologist and obstetrician. ``And unless he was
after birth control pills for his girlfriend, there's absolutely
nothing for him to take.''
   The 180-pound suspect was lodged about midway down the chimney.
Officer Wade Kollar stood on the rooftop of a single-story
structure to advise him of his right to remain silent, according to
police reports.
   ``We wore out all of the Christmas jokes,'' said Fire Department
Lt. Rob Edwards.
   After an alarm was triggered, an officer scaled the building and
discovered the suspect, police spokesman George Pinckney said.
   Edwards said the burglar apparently slipped, fell down the chute
and got caught with one arm pinned at his side.
</TEXT>
