<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Personnel     03-25 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Personnel,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Nominates Taft as NATO Ambassador</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William H. Taft IV, acting defense secretary
for the first two months of the Bush administration, is President
Bush's nominee as the U.S. representative to NATO.
   In making the announcement Friday, Bush also said he would
nominate former Republican Sen. Chic Hecht of Nevada to be
ambassador to the Bahamas. Both nominations, as well as several
others announced by the White House, require Senate confirmation.
   At the same time Bush took the unusual step of withdrawing his
earlier nomination of Pentagon official Richard L. Armitage as
assistant secretary of state for East Asian and Pacific affairs.
The president picked Richard H. Solomon for the post instead.
   Bush said Armitage would remain at the Pentagon ``in a senior
position which will be announced at a later date.''
   Administration sources, who spoke on the condition of anonymity,
have said that Cheney has asked Armitage to stay on, possibly as
secretary of the Navy.
   Hecht served one term in the Senate but was defeated in a
re-election bid last year by Democrat Richard H. Bryan, a former
Nevada governor. Hecht would succeed Carol Boyd Hallett.
   Taft, 43, oversaw daily Pentagon operations as acting defense
secretary during the confirmation process for John Tower.
   The great-grandson of the nation's 27th president, Taft has been
deputy defense secretary since 1984, serving under defense
secretaries Caspar Weinberger and Frank Carlucci.
   Taft would have ambassadorial status and would succeed Alton
Keel as the permanent U.S. representative to the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization.
   Solomon would succeed Gaston Sigur Jr. He has been director of
the State Department's policy and planning staff since 1986.
   A former political science professor at the University of
Michigan, Solomon also was a senior staff member on the National
Security Administration in the Nixon administration. From 1976 to
1986, he was the head of the Rand Corp.'s political science
department.
   In other personnel announcements, the White House said Bush
would nominate:
   _Charles E. Redman, who has served as assistant secretary of
state for public affairs and its chief spokesman since 1986, to be
ambassador to Sweden. He would succeed Gregory J. Newell.
   _Joseph B. Gildenhorn, a Washington lawyer and real estate
executive, to be ambassador to Switzerland. He would succeed Philip
D. Winn.
   _Paul Matthews Cleveland, a former ambassador to New Zealand and
to Western Samoa, to be ambassador to Malaysia. He would succeed
John Cameron Monjo.
   _John J. Maresca, deputy assistant defense secretary for
European and NATO policy, as chief of the U.S. delegation to the
recently opened East-West talks in Geneva intended to reduce
tensions in Western Europe.
   _Edward Nokonan Ney to be ambassador to Canada. Since 1986, he
has been vice chairman of Paine Webber Group Inc. and was a member
of the Grace Commission, which studied waste and inefficiencies in
government. He would succeed Thomas Michael Tolliver Niles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
