<FIRST>d a BC-Opera     03-25 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Opera,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Met's `Die Walkure' Is Thrillingly Sung</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maybe the singers at the Metropolitan Opera were
especially ``up'' for their performances Friday night because they
were being videotaped. Whatever the reason, the season's first
performance of ``Die Walkure'' was glorious.
   In the first act, tenor Gary Lakes as Siegmund, soprano Jessye
Norman as Sieglinde and bass Matti Salminen as her husband,
Hunding, all displayed rich, even lush voices.
   Wotan, leader of the gods, comes into the picture in Act 2. He
was sung by James Morris, whose voice is brighter than many basses
who sing Wotan. His wife, Fricka, was sung by Christa Ludwig in a
way that sounded more like explaining than laying down the law.
   Hildegard Behrens, as Wotan's warrior daughter, Brunnhilde, was
girlishly exuberant at first. Later, when she has less to be
exuberant about, she maintained an attractive girlish quality in
her singing.
   A variety of vocal shadings kept the singing interesting. Miss
Norman particularly had many colors and textures in her singing.
   Morris, Salminen and Miss Norman were singing their parts at the
Met for the first time.
   All of the Valkyries sang well. The orchestra played beautifully
under the baton of James Levine. Orchestral interludes were
lovingly presented. Their tempo seemed slow at first but it was
never slack.
   Another performance of ``Die Walkure'' this season will be taped
also, and the other three of Wagner's ``Ring Cycle'' operas will be
videotaped next season. The four will be televised by PBS in June
1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
