<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-89 0157EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ChambersSentencing     03-25 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chambers Sentencing,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sentencing Of Gang Members Doesn't End Drug Problem, Prosecutors
Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUSTIN BURKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities said they scored a big victory when
nine members of what was once the city's largest drug ring received
lengthy federal prison terms, but they added that the fight is far
from over.
   ``It's a continuing problem, and I'm not going to say we've
turned the corner yet,'' said U.S. Attorney Roy C. Hayes, who
prosecuted the case. ``But we've made a significant dent.''
   U.S. District Judge Richard F. Suhrheinrich gave the maximum
prison term to eight of the nine Chambers Brothers gang members
sentenced Friday. The members were convicted Oct. 28 following a
six-week trial.
   ``There are crimes against civilization for which there is no
excuse ... and this is one them,'' Suhrheinrich said. ``How can we
have any regard for people who are destroying future generations?''
   So far, no drug gang has succeeded in replacing the Chambers
Brothers, although many are vying for the role, Hayes said.
   ``I'm hoping that the era of big drug gangs in Detroit has ended
with this trial,'' Hayes said. ``What we've shown is that a big,
powerful and violent drug gang can be put out of business.''
   There is no shortage of drug suspects, according to police
statistics. Drug-related arrests in Detroit increased 123 percent
in the 12 months ending Nov. 30, 1988, compared with the same
12-month period the previous year, police spokesman Christopher
Buck said.
   Buck said the increase does not mean the drug problem in Detroit
has worsened. The rise in drug arrests from 4,102 in 1986-87 to
9,520 in 1987-88 was due primarily to an anti-crack offensive that
helped reduce overall crime, he said.
   Suhrheinrich said he imposed the maximum sentence possible in
most cases because of the seriousness of the crack threat in
Detroit.
   ``It (crack) is indeed doing to our poor people what no person
could do. It is enslaving them,'' Suhrheinrich said before
sentencing. ``It's doing what Hitler could never do to us.''
   Larry Chambers, 39, the reputed leader of the gang, was
sentenced to life in prison and a $250,000 fine for operating a
continuing criminal enterprise.
   Billy Joe Chambers, 26, was sentenced to more than 45 years and
a $500,000 fine for conspiracy and operating a continuing criminal
enterprise.
   Otis Chambers was sentenced to more than 27 years and a $350,000
fine for conspiracy and Willie Chambers was sentenced to more than
21 years and a $350,000 fine for conspiracy and tax evasion.
   Also convicted of conspiracy and sentenced Friday were gang
members Eric L. Wilkins, more than 33 years in prison; Elaine
Coleman Lucas, 10 years; Belinda Lumpkin, 25 years, Jerry Gant, 30
years, and Marshall Glenn, 30 years.
   Only Lucas received less than the maximum sentence because of
her minor role in the ring, the judge said.
   The Chambers Brothers gang was notorious for its corporatelike
structure, according to witnesses' testimony. The ring supplied
cocaine to as many as half of Detroit's estimated 1,000 crack
houses from 1982 until 1988, prosecutors said.
   Hayes said the stiff sentences will send an important message to
would-be drug dealers battling to fill the void created by breakup
of the Chambers gang.
   Police alone can't stem the tide of drugs in Detroit,
Suhrheinrich said in an often emotional 20-minute pre-sentencing
speech.
   ``Where is the community? Where is the press? Where is the
mayor? Where is the governor? Where is the president?''
Suhrheinrich said. ``Until we in the United States demand and are
allowed to walk down streets without drug dealers putting us in
fear, then we will never improve our institutions.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
