<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     03-25 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Fruit Cleared For Import</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration has cleared
the way for Chilean apples, peaches and plums to be sold to U.S.
markets after they are inspected for evidence of cyanide poisoning.
   Food graders should begin inspecting Chilean apples, peaches and
plums this weekend, an FDA spokesman said on Friday.
   Import restrictions were lifted on pears and nectarines from
Chile on Tuesday, and on grapes and berries last Friday, allowing
the fruit to be released for sale after 5 percent of each shipment
is inspected and found free from cyanide.
   Grapes, which constitute 70 percent of the fruit Chile sends to
the United States, began appearing on produce shelves of U.S.
stores this week after a two-week absence due to the
cyanide-poisoning scare.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Secretary Tells Scientists to Devise Cleanup Plan</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy Secretary James D. Watkins is directing
his department to devote more attention to new methods of nuclear
waste cleanup to support a plan to establish cleanup priorities and
schedules over the next five years.
   Watkins wrote members of Congress that he hopes to have the
cleanup plan in place by August.
   During the next five years, ``immediate problems'' will be
``corrected'' and detailed long-term cleanup plans will be drawn up
for each site, spokesman Phil Keif said Friday.
   The department produces nuclear weapons in at least 16
laboratories and factories in 12 states. Waste, both nuclear and
chemical, generated since the formation of the World War II
Manhattan Project in 1942 has resulted in massive contamination of
some areas around the facilities.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Plans Unveiled to Speed Americans' Returns</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Customs Service announced plans
Friday to help speed Americans through the federal inspection
process at four major airports when they return from abroad.
   Passengers bringing back nothing that must be declared generally
will be able to present their passport to an immigration inspector,
claim their baggage and leave without a stop at Customs. Passengers
with items to declare will make only a brief stop at a Customs or
Agriculture station before being cleared, the agency said.
   The program is scheduled to begin this summer at Los Angeles'
Tom Bradley International Terminal, San Francisco International
Airport and Chicago's O'Hare International Airport. It will start
later this year at Miami International Airport, the agency said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>IRS Modifies Diesel Tax Collection For Farmers, Off-Road Users</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Internal Revenue Service has bowing to
pressure from farm state lawmakers and allowed small wholesalers
and some retailers to make sales of diesel fuel without the payment
of tax.
   In issuing its notice on Friday, the IRS agreed to lower the
standards for wholesaler distributors ad some retailers to qualify
for an exemption from the 15.1-cent-a-gallon tax for sales to
farmers, fishermen and others who buy diesel for off-road use.
   For example, one new standard will allow distributors to
automatically qualify for an exemption if at least 70 percent of
their bulk sales of diesel are to users who do not have to pay the
tax, such as farmers. A key change will define bulk sales as those
of at least 25 gallons involving storage tanks of 50 gallons or
more.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Union Challenges Education Department's Drug Test Plan</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A union representing 3,000 Education
Department workers has filed a court challenge to the department's
plans to begin a random drug-testing program next month.
   The suit, filed in U.S. District Court here Thursday, is the
latest of more than a half-dozen attempts by the American
Federation of Government Employees to block drug-testing programs
in federal departments and agencies.
   A union spokeswoman said the Education Department on Feb. 21
distributed to employees a notice that the testing program would
begin on or after April 21. Federal agencies, as part of their
compliance with an executive order issued by then-President Reagan
requiring them to draft drug-testing programs, routinely give
employees 60 days' notice before beginning testing.
</TEXT>
