<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clint Eastwood and Pee Wee Herman in a movie
together?
   That's what USA Weekend magazine readers would like to see.
   The magazine polled its readers to see how they would run things
if they ran the movie business.
   The favorites for a big-screen comeback were E.T., the space
creature who rocketed to fame in 1982, and Katharine Hepburn, who
made her film debut in 1932.
   In a questionnaire filled out by more than 15,000 readers, E.T.
and Miss Hepburn each received 29 percent of the vote. Marlon
Brando got 18 percent.
   The real-life person readers would like to see portrayed on film
is Donald Trump. The real estate billionaire got an overwhelming 57
percent of the ballots, the magazine reports in its March 24-26
issue.
   The odd couple suggestion of tough guy Eastwood and comedian
Herman came from 48 percent of the respondents.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PIGEON FORGE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country singers Porter Wagoner and
Dolly Parton will appear on stage together for the first time in 10
years.
   The pair, who used to sing on television's ``The Porter Wagoner
Show'' and appeared together at the the Grand Ole Opry during the
1960s and '70s, will revive duets such as ``The Last Thing On My
Mind'' and ``Hanging Onto Nothin','' said Dan Rohman, a spokesman
for Parton's theme park, Dollywood.
   The two split in 1976 following public bickering over their
business partnership.
   The Dollywood concerts _ two on April 29 and two the following
day _ will have each performing alone, then a finale in which they
sing together, Rohman said.
   The concerts launch the fourth season for Dollywood in the east
Tennessee hills, where she grew up.
