<FIRST>u a AM-AssaultRifles     03-25 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Assault Rifles,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stunned Agency Reverses Permission Granted to Import 400,000 Guns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Treasury Department's bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms has ordered the Customs Service to halt
shipments of more than 400,000 military-style assault weapons at
the nation's borders, a newspaper reported.
   Bureau officials, stunned that hundreds of thousands of weapons
such as the AK-47 had already been approved for import, in effect
is rescinding that approval, the Los Angeles Times reported in its
Saturday editions.
   The action goes beyond steps taken earlier in March when the
Bush administration announced a temporary ban on issuing of new
permits for five types assault weapon, including the AK-47, the
weapon used earlier this year in a massacre of schoolchildren in
Stockton, Calif.
   William T. Drake, a top official at ATF, acknowledged in an
interview with the Times that the move would be controversial. But
he said an internal audit detailing the vast extent of imports
already authorized had persuaded the agency to take the emergency
action.
   The bureau declined to disclose how many weapons have been
approved for import, but an unidentified Customs Service source
cited by the Times said the number is more than 400,000.
   The weapons were not affected by the moratorium, which only
blocked approval of new applications for weapons imports. When the
action was taken, new applications to import 110,000 assault
weapons were pending.
   The moratorium will be lifted only if importers can prove that
the weapons are used generally for sporting purposes.
   About 70,000 assault rifles have been imported into the United
STates in the last three years, according to the agency.
   The ATF order was transmitted orally Thursday and made formal in
a directive issued by Drake on Friday.
</TEXT>
