<FIRST>r i PM-Stevenson'sIsland     03-25 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stevenson's Island,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Isle That May Have Inspired `Treasure Island' Sold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH BERWICK, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An island in the Firth of Forth
that may have inspired Robert Louis Stevenson's ``Treasure Island''
has been purchased by admirers of its resident seabirds.
   The Royal Society for the Preservation of Birds said Friday it
had purchased 12-acre Fidra island for $3,200 from the Northern
Lighthouse Board, whose former employees include Stevenson's father.
   ``Robert Louis Stevenson was brought up in Edinburgh, and his
family spent holidays for many years at North Berwick,'' said Iain
Illingworth, the society's reserves manager for east Scotland.
   Fidra, 15 miles east of Edinburgh and a half-mile off shore in
the river Forth, has a 56-foot high lighthouse and ruins of a
12th-century chapel dedicated to St. Nicholas.
   ``I don't think there is any very hard evidence, but it is
believed that it is the inspiration for `Treasure Island,'''
Illingworth said.
   The treeless island's 50-foot cliffs are ``a very important site
for nesting seabirds, and it's important that it be allowed to
carry on,'' said Illingworth. Among the residents are puffins,
kittiwakes, razorbills, guillemots, fulmars and shags.
   More than 200 eider duck nests were found on the island last
year, he said.
   ``It's only sort of 15 miles from Edinburgh, yet it's a jewel in
the Firth of Forth. Because it is very little visited and it has
these cliffs, it's an excellent place for birds to breed,''
Illingworth said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
