<FIRST>r a PM-ThinBlueLine     03-25 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thin Blue Line,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Adams' First Full Day Back Home Is A Quiet One</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Randall Dale Adams attended a quiet family
gathering and toured his hometown during his first full day back
since his release from prison.
   But the man who spent 12 years behind bars in Texas for a crime
he says he didn't commit appeared less concerned about the future
than about adjusting to the life he left in 1977 _ when he was
sentenced to death.
   ``To be able to dress like a human being again _ that adds to
your self-confidence,'' Adams said Friday at a relative's home
south of Columbus. ``To be able to go out among people and not be
an inmate, a convict, that improves (your outlook).''
   Adams' case had garnered wide attention after ``The Thin Blue
Line,'' a documentary, raised doubts about his guilt in the
shooting death of Dallas officer Robert Wood.
   He came within three days of execution in 1980 for the murder
before his sentence was commuted to life in prison.
   At the family gathering, Adams told Columbus television station
WBNS that he received a card containing a check from an anonymous
source in the mail Friday. He didn't reveal the amount of the check.
   Adams, 40, who worked as a clerk in the prison maintenance
office and earned an associate degree in general studies while
imprisoned, said he has no immediate job plans. Columbus Mayor Dana
Rinehart has offered him unspecified employment with the city.
   He was greeted by yellow ribbons and rousing cheers when he
returned Thursday to Columbus.
   On March 1, the Texas Court of Criminal Appeals had ordered a
new trial for him, saying a witness had lied and a prosecutor
suppressed evidence. And on Thursday, the Dallas County, Texas,
district attorney dropped the case against him, citing a lack of
evidence.
   Adams spent much of his day out of the public eye.
   All was quiet at the blue and white trailer home on the city's
west side where Adams' mother, Mildred, has lived since she sold
her house in suburban Grove City to help pay her son's legal bills.
   Mrs. Adams said her son embarked on a tour of the city early in
the morning with filmmaker Errol Morris, who directed ``The Thin
Blue Line.''
   In Texas, a juror said she was convinced she had erred in
declaring Adams guilty.
   ``If he had gone to the death chamber and all this had come out
later, that would have been a horrible thing to have on my
conscience,'' said Bette Jane Fain, the jury forewoman at Adams'
1977 trial.
</TEXT>
