<HEAD>Rebels Claim Downing Of Plane Carrying Government Troops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   UNITA guerrillas claim to have shot down
a Soviet-built transport plane supplying government troops in
southern Angola.
   A statement monitored in Lisbon from the rebel's stronghold in
Jamba, Angola, said the Ilyushin Il-76 aircraft was struck Friday
by UNITA anti-aircraft fire and crashed near Menongue. The
statement, which said government forces are massing in the south,
did not elaborate.
   There was no immediate comment from the government.
   UNITA _ the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola
_ has been fighting a civil war against the Angolan government
since shortly after the country gained independence from Portugal
in 1975.
   Rebel leader Jonas Savimbi rejects a U.S.-sponsored peace
agreement signed last December in which 50,000 Cuban troops
supporting the Marxist-orientated government have began leaving
Angola.
   Under the terms of the agreement, South Africa pledges to halt
military aid to UNITA and withdraw from neighboring Namibia, which
South African troops used as a base for raids into Angola in
support of Savimbi.
   The United States continues to assist the rebels, while the
Soviet Union supplies government forces.
