<HEAD>U.S. Air Force Mistakenly Drops Dummy Bomb On Farm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOYKO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Air Force plane mistakenly dropped a dummy
bomb on a dairy pasture last week during bombing drills, the
Defense Facilities Administration office said today.
   The March 16 mishap occurred when an F-16 fighter jet dropped a
25-pound non-explosive bomb during bombing practice drills, said
Masayuki Sato of the Defense Facilities Administration office.
   The bomb landed 40 feet from a dormitory for farm workers but no
damage was reported, he said.
   Sato said the U.S. Air Force reported the accident was due to
human error, not mechanical failure, and apologized. The U.S.
military declined to identify the pilot.
   F-16 fighter planes routinely engage in bombing drills at a
practice range 25 miles north of Misawa Air Base, 350 miles
northwest of Tokyo.
   Kyodo News Service said the mishap occurred near a proposed
nuclear fuel reprocessing center, which local residents have
protested as dangerous because it is too close to the military base.
   The area of the proposed plant, to be partially opened in 1991,
is within the area where the U.S. Air Force makes 42,000 flights a
year, the project's contractors were quoted as telling Kyodo.
