<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-89 0241EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Steinberg     03-25 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steinberg,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Steinberg Gets Maximum Sentence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joel Steinberg, convicted of killing his
illegally adopted daughter, has been sentenced to the maximum 8 1-3
to 25 years in prison after being described as callous, selfish and
manipulative.
   The disbarred attorney slumped in resignation upon hearing state
Supreme Court Justice Harold Rothwax issue the sentence for his
manslaughter conviction in the November 1987 death of 6-year-old
Lisa.
   The defendant had spent nearly 20 minutes protesting his
innocence, saying he was guilty only of an ``error in judgment''
for not immediately getting medical help for the child when she
fell unconscious.
   Near tears and almost pleading, Steinberg told Rothwax that he
never hit Lisa and said she received ``constant love.''
   ``Those children were not locked in a house of horror,''
Steinberg said of Lisa and the baby boy he called Mitchell, also
illegally adopted.
   But Assistant District Attorney John McCusker told the court
Lisa's death was a result of Steinberg's ``life of violence,
selfishness and self-gratification at the expense of other people.''
   ``Mr. Steinberg has shown not one ounce of remorse for killing
Elisabeth,'' McCusker said.
   ``I understand the meaning of remorse,'' said Steinberg, who had
not testified at the trial. ``I have remorse about losing my life.
   ``I feel that pain every day. It's my loss. I'm the victim.''
   Hedda Nussbaum, Steinberg's battered former live-in companion
and the key prosecution witness against him, watched the sentencing
on television at the Manhattan office of her lawyer, Betty
Levinson. She heard Steinberg say Lisa was fine when he left her
with Ms. Nussbaum, 46, and went to dinner with a friend.
   ``He just got up there and lied and she's furious,'' Ms.
Levinson said of Ms. Nussbaum's reaction. ``He was weaving together
this totally untrue and fantastic rendition of what happened.''
   Steinberg, 47, said Lisa received ``constant nurturing, constant
caring, constant love'' and described their life in a Greenwich
Village townhouse where Mark Twain once lived as ``joyous, superb,
delightful.''
   Steinberg denied hitting the child, but said, ``I don't deny
that during the course of administering CPR, OK, I could have
caused some'' injury.
   He dispassionately discussed the technical aspects of Lisa's
bruises more as a lawyer, rather than a defendant.
   Steinberg suddenly stopped and told Rothwax, ``Your honor is
laughing.''
   ``I'm not laughing,'' the judge. ``I'm just astonished.''
   At several points during Steinberg's discussion of Lisa, her
natural mother Michele Launders, and Graceann Smigiel, the boy's
maternal grandmother, wept.
   Steinberg smiled, chuckled and fidgeted while his lawyers
offered lengthy presentencing motions, all of which were denied by
Rothwax.
   In a brief preamble to the sentence, Rothwax said Steinberg's
``extraordinary narcissism and self-involvement, his extreme need
to control ... led him to become the instrument of Lisa's death.''
   The judge also fined Steinberg $5,000 and recommended against
parole.
   Steinberg has been held without bail since his arrest Nov. 2,
1987. So he will eligible for parole in seven years, having already
served 16 months of the 8 1-3-year minimum sentence.
   Even without parole, New York's general practice would allow
Steinberg to serve only two-thirds of his maximum _ 16 years and
eight months in this case _ since he can earn one-third of his
sentence off for good behavior.
   Rothwax received hundreds of letters _ from adoptive parents,
childless couples and people abused as children _ urging him to
give Steinberg the maximum term.
   Perry Reich, a attorney for Steinberg, said a notice of appeal
was filed Friday, adding, ``We're very optimistic. It is fair to
say this was just round one.''
</TEXT>
