<HEAD>Leper Gives Birth Outside Hospital That Turned Her Away</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman with leprosy gave birth outside
the gates of a Red Cross hospital that had hours earlier turned her
away, an official said today.
   Col. Krishan Gulati said a doctor at the Family Welfare and
Children's Hospital in suburban New Delhi refused Wednesday to
admit the 27-year-old woman for fear her open wounds would infect
its only operating room.
   Gulati, head of the local chapter of the Red Cross Society, said
the woman later that day delivered a girl just outside the hospital.
   Residents of a nearby leper colony demonstrated outside the
hospital Friday to demand action against the doctor who refused to
admit the woman. Gulati said the hospital will no longer refuse
such patients.
   The couple lives near the hospital in Seemapuri, a New Delhi
suburb and the largest leprosy colony in northern India. About
5,000 lepers live there.
   Gulati said the young mother was eventually admitted to a ward
in the 50-bed hospital and discharged Friday.
