<FIRST>r i PM-PollutionConcert     03-25 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pollution Concert,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rock Stars Give Anti-Pollution Concert To 200,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rock groups Midnight Oil, INXS and
Icehouse gave a concert to 200,000 people that raised $80,000 to
help stop pollution of this city's famed beaches.
   The Turn Back The Tide concert Friday at Bondi Beach also
included Americans Joe Walsh and Christopher Cross and the
Australian bands Rose Tatoo and the Divynls.
   Untreated sewage and high levels of pollution have recently been
detected off several Sydney beaches. Viruses capable of causing
meningitis and myocarditis and fish with high mercury levels have
been discovered off Bondi.
   ``The politicians will learn that they will lose elections if
they continue to pollute the ocean,'' concert organizer Richard
Clugston said.
   Rock singer John Farnham told the crowd he had met with New
South Wales state environmental minister Tim Moore and members of
the Water Board, and ``they told us that the sewage they pumped
into the sea was diluted one part in ten. They expect us to swim in
that ?''
   Sydney disc jockey Jonathon Coleman described the concert as
``Australia's Woodstock against poo (pollution).''
