<FIRST>u i PM-India-Bomb     03-25 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Bomb,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Explodes In Marketplace, 1 Dead, 6 Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A powerful bomb strapped on an abandoned
bicycle exploded today in a crowded Indian market, killing at least
one person and injuring six, authorities in the northern state of
Punjab said.
   No one claimed responsibility for the explosion, but police
blamed Sikh extremists pressing their 7-year campaign for a
separate homeland.
   Police said the bomb went off at a busy intersection in Katra
Jailmal Singh, one of the main markets in the city's old, walled
section. The market also is near the Golden Temple, the Sikhs'
holiest shrine.
   The explosion, heard two miles away, caused widespread damage to
shops and cars, police said.
   Sikhs, whose faith is rooted both in Hinduism and Islam,
outnumber Hindus in Punjab, a rich farming state bordering
Pakistan. But they comprise only 2 percent of the nationwide
population of 880 million. Hindus make up 82 percent of the
country's populace.
   Militant Sikhs launched their separatist campaign in 1982, and
the death toll has escalated each year.
   In 1988, at least 2,400 people were killed by Sikh extremists in
Punjab. At least 457 people have died so far this year.
</TEXT>
