<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     03-25 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trumpeter Warren Gale has played ``Zip a
Dee Doo Dah'' at least 33,000 times, which adds up to about a
thousand times for each year he worked at Disneyland before
retiring.
   Main Street USA has been Gale's stage, but it's time to slow
down, he said.
   With a bad back, bad feet and a little extra weight, Gale, 68,
said ``marching up and down that street is getting harder every
day.''
   Gale has been part of the ``World Famous Disneyland Band'' since
1955, when Disneyland's Magic Kingdom opened in Orange County. Gale
retired Friday.
   He was one of only a few original employees at the park. And one
of the more accomplished, amusement park officials said.
   ``Warren is one of the finest trumpet players in the world,''
said Dave Warble, Disneyland's head conductor for the past six
years. ``When he plays a solo _ and this is every day, every set _
everyone stops and listens. He has a style uniquely his own; it
can't be duplicated. He is so correct musically and artistically,
we just sit there in awe of him.
   ``He's the E.F. Hutton of the trumpet,'' Warble said. ``When he
plays, people listen.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even with a will, there's no way to inherit
University of Nebraska football season tickets without benefit of
marriage.
   A new university policy permits transfer of season tickets to
spouses or, in the event of death, to surviving spouses.
   The previous policy had allowed season tickets to be passed on
to sons, daughters or other relatives.
   ``The season ticket renewal policy was changed after a long and
careful study of the administration problems caused by the old
policy,'' said Athletic Director Bob Devaney.
   ``We've had plenty of complaints from loyal alums and loyal fans
who were never able to procure season tickets because they were
being handed from generation to generation.
   ``There are too many good people who have been stuck buying
tickets game-by-game and have been waiting a long time to get
season tickets without much hope because there weren't any season
tickets being freed up,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN RAFAEL, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Marin County Humane Society wants
every pet owner to make sure their dog or cat has a chip on its
shoulder.
   The Society plans to implant microchips into the animals to
serve as electronic nameplates for instant identification.
   Starting in a few weeks, lost, stolen or strayed pets which are
turned in to the county animal shelter will be injected into the
shoulder with a $40 rice grain-sized chip imprinted with the
critter's 10-digit I.D. number.
   With the wave of an electronic wand, Rover's or Fluffy's
numbered codes for names, addresses and telephone numbers show up
on a screen, and the animal is as good as headed home.
   Mary Wright of the society said the scanning device will be run
over the chip which will be imbedded in the animal's shoulder ``and
it makes a little beep _ just like at the check stand. It's very
high tech.''
   Some 2,500 stray pets, mostly dogs and cats, are destroyed each
year at the Marin shelter, and the new system could save at least
some of them, said Wright.
</TEXT>
