<FIRST>r a PM-Toddler-MineShaft     03-25 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Toddler-Mine Shaft,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colorado Toddler Killed in Fall Down Mine Shaft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CENTRAL CITY, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 2-year-old boy wandered away from
his home in this historic silver mining town and fell to his death
in a nearby abandoned mine shaft, authorities said.
   Gilpin County Coroner Dick Allen said the child, identified as
Michael Mills, apparently was killed instantly from massive head
injuries.
   John Rittenhouse, search coordinator for the Gilpin County
Search and Rescue Team, said the boy's body was found Friday night
about 150 to 200 feet down the shaft, lodged among timbers and
rocks. He said the shaft went far below that point.
   Central City, in the foothills of the Rocky Mountains about 30
miles west of Denver, was a silver mining boom town from the
mid-1800s till the turn of the century.
   Authorities said probably 5,000 abandoned mine shafts are in the
area, many of them uncovered.
   The boy had been playing in his yard with his older sister, whom
Rittenhouse described as being in her 20s.
   ``There was a phone call and when she came back out he was gone.
We were called out about 2:45 p.m. ... We followed his tracks up to
an abandoned mine shaft that's maybe 100 yards behind his house and
found an area that something apparently had slid down into the mine
shaft,'' Rittenhouse said.
   The mine rescue unit was then called out and an access road had
to be bulldozed about 100 yards up a hill to the shaft site, he
said.
   A special boom truck rigged with cable winch and an enclosed
cage was brought to the mouth of the shaft.
   Two men were lowered in the cage about 10 p.m.
   ``We got down about 50 feet with the cage and the shaft narrowed
to the point the cage wouldn't go any furthur,'' Rittenhouse said.
``At that point we pulled it up and hooked a smaller ore bucket to
our boom truck and lowered it down with two men in it. We were able
to get down to the boy.''
   The boy's body was found about 10:40 p.m., Rittenhouse said.
   About 30 rescue workers participated in the search under the
bright glare of floodlights in mild weather.
</TEXT>
