<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-89 0550EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MissingBoat     03-25 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Missing Boat,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Search Fails To Produce Any Clue to Boat's Fate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coast Guard and Navy have called off
their search for a 52-foot sport fishing yacht with 10 people on
board, and authorities said they have not ruled out a possible hoax.
   Coast Guard radio operators monitored a distress call about 9:30
p.m. Thursday in which the caller said the boat was foundering in
heavy seas 5 miles off of Virginia Beach.
   Two minutes later, a second and final transmission from the boat
Blue Goose stated that the vessel was sinking and all aboard had
donned life vests and were entering the water. Coast Guard attempts
to call the vessel got no response.
   ``We completely scoured the area, covered it countless times,''
said Lt. j.g. Carlyle A. Blomme, commander of the Coast Guard
cutter Point Huron.
   The 20-hour search was suspended Friday evening.
   ``We didn't find anything; no coolers, no nothing, just lots of
fog,'' Blomme said. ``Due to the lack of evidence, we can't rule
out a hoax. But when lives are concerned, we have to search.''
   Norfolk's regional office of the Federal Communications
Commission was ``watching the case to determine whether this is a
possible hoax,'' said J.J. Freeman, the FCC's engineer in charge.
``We're already in contact with the Coast Guard. They must treat
every call as a bonified emergency.''
   Broadcast of a fraudulent mayday is a federal offense and
carries a maximum penalty of a $100,000 fine and one year in
prison, according to federal officials.
   Three Coast Guard cutters, a helicopter and two Navy ships
searched for the vessel Friday in seas that rose to 10 to 12 feet
and in dense fog that sometimes produced zero visibility.
   Vessels criss-crossed an 85-square-mile area, parts of it three
and four times, Coast Guard Lt. Walter T. Hunnings said.
   The Coast Guard also ran computer checks on all registered
vessels with the name Blue Goose. But of the 35 or so with that
name on the Atlantic Coast, none matched the length and make of the
craft described in the distress call.
</TEXT>
