<HEAD>Snow Blankets Northern New England, Rain Falls Along Pacific Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Winter hung on in parts of New England, while rain drenched the
northern and central Pacific Coast.
   Snow blanketed the northern half of New England, with up to a
foot falling on the highest elevations of Vermont. Snowfall during
the 6 hours ending 1 a.m. EST included 5 inches at Concord, N.H.,
and 3 inches at Lebanon, N.Y., and Portland, Maine.
   The snow changed to rain in southern New England, southern New
York State, northern New Jersey and northeast Pennsylvania.
   Rain also fell over the northern and central Pacific Coast and
light rain was scattered over the southern coast of California.
   Elsewhere, rain fell from western upper Michigan across northern
Wisconsin.
   Heavier rainfall during the 6 hours ending at 1 a.m. EST
included 1.19 inches at Providence, R.I., and 1.1 inches at
Chatham, Mass.
   Today's forecast called for rain extending from the Pacific
Coast across much of the northern and central Plateau; rain in the
northern Atlantic Coast states; and snow in northern Maine.
   Predicted highs: 40s and 50s from New England across the Great
Lakes and the upper Mississippi Valley, North Dakota, eastern South
Dakota, the upper Missouri Valley, the Rockies, the Great Basin and
the northern two-thirds of the Pacific Coast; 80s in the Florida
Peninsula, Texas and the desert Southwest; and the 60s and 70s
elsewhere.
