<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-89 0609EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon     03-25 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Christians Duel Syrians, Druse with Rockets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian army units fought all-night
artillery and rocket battles with Syrian army gunners and allied
Druse militiamen in the Beirut area. Police today reported six
people killed and 31 wounded.
   The new casualties raised the toll to 87 people killed and 284
wounded since March 8, when clashes broke out between Gen. Michel
Aoun's Christian troops and militiamen of Druse warlord Walid
Jumblatt's Progressive Socialist Party. Syrian troops earlier this
week joined Jumblatt's forces in battles.
   Aoun also leads a Christian Cabinet that rivals a Moslem
government for control of this divided nation, which has endured 14
years of civil war.
   A police spokesman, who cannot be identified under standing
rules, said the new casualties were civilians. The spokesman said
no Christian soldiers were injured, and he knew nothing of any
casualties on the other side.
   The independent daily newspaper An-Nahar, published in
Syrian-policed Moslem west Beirut, said Aoun's gunners, operating
U.S.-designed 155mm howitzers, scored direct hits on Syrian army
positions in seven towns and villages around Beirut. It gave no
casualty figures.
   Syrian army gunners pounded Christian towns northeast of Beirut
with 107mm Soviet-designed Grad rockets from multi-barrelled
launchers deployed along mountains south and east of the capital.
   The barrage several times reached as high as 80 rounds a minute
before the artillery duel tapered off into sporadic exchanges at
daybreak, the police spokesman said.
   Syria, the main powerbroker in Lebanon, keeps 40,000 troops in
Lebanon under a 1976 Arab League mandate to end the civil war.
   Flashes from artillery explosions cut the darkness as the thuds
of bombardment shook Beirut and surrounding areas.
   The clashes have followed a pattern of massive nighttime
shelling followed by daytime lulls, apparently to give people a
chance to buy food and other supplies.
   Denise Khater, an executive secretary in the Christian suburb of
Baabda, said:``It was raining rockets at Baabda. Several times I
thought the building would collapse on the basement where we were
hiding.''
   Bank employee Elie Badran said Christian east Beirut's densely
populated Ashrafiyeh district also came under ferocious bombardment
overnight but that most people had taken refuge in basements and
bomb shelters before dusk.
   ``We've installed a television set in the basement of our
building. We also have beds, mattresses and blankets in addition to
a variety of medicines, first aid equipment and water supply,'' he
said.
   The artillery duel escalated sharply Friday evening after Aoun
rejected a truce with the Syrian and Jumblatt's forces and vowed to
drive the Syrian army out of Lebanon even if the fighting destroys
Beirut.
   The confrontation broke out earlier this month after Aoun
decided to blockade illegal militia-run ports along Lebanon's
coast. The militias have been skimming tax revenues the government
would otherwise collect there.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
