<FIRST>r a PM-HalcionLawsuit     03-25 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Halcion Lawsuit,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Sues Upjohn Corp., Claims Drug Prompted Slaying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who claims she shot her
82-year-old mother eight times in the head and neck in a
``homicidal compulsion'' induced by the drug Halcion has filed a
$21 million federal lawsuit against Upjohn Corp.
   Ilo Marie Grundberg says she was suffering a severe case of
``Halcion intoxication'' when she shot and killed Mildred Coats on
June 19, 1988, according to the lawsuit filed in U.S. District
Court on Friday.
   Grundberg, who once shared a home with her mother in the
southern Utah city of Hurricane, faced a second-degree murder
charge until a judge dismissed the case, ruling the killing was the
result of her addiction to the prescription drug used in treating
insomnia.
   Grundberg is joined in the lawsuit by her daughter, Janice Gray,
who both now live in Yucaipa, Calif. Gray represents Coats' estate.
   The lawsuit contends that Upjohn of Kalamazoo, Mich., knew or
should have known that Halcion, known generically as triazolam,
could cause intoxication in the user even when properly prescribed
and used ``according to the advice and directions supplied by the
defendant.''
   Among the possible reactions, the lawsuit claims, are ``severe
depression, hallucinations, psychosis, organic brain damage,
bizarre and profoundly disturbed behavior, amnesia'' and other side
effects which, ``if not promptly discovered and treated, can lead
to personal injury and death to the user and others in contact with
the user.''
   Upjohn spokeswoman Nancy Heitzman declined to discuss the
lawsuit Friday, saying company policy prohibited comment on pending
litigation.
   Grundberg, 57, admitted that on the night of her mother's death,
she slipped a birthday card into the sleeping woman's hand _ the
next day was her 83rd birthday _ then shot her with a .22-caliber
revolver.
   She then wrote a confession saying she loved her mother, but
killed her to spare her from what she described as troubled
financial times ahead. She then called police.
   An investigation, however, revealed the women were well off
financially and that Coats had signed over all her assets to
Grundberg. Police said they had no motive for the shooting.
</TEXT>
