<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-89 0624EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-NYCCrime     03-25 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NYC Crime,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two People a Day Died in Drug-Related Slayings, Stats Show</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly two people a day were killed last year in
drug-related slayings in the nation's largest city, making up
almost 37 percent of the record 1,896 homicides, police said.
   In addition, the epidemic of crack, a powerful form of cocaine,
was responsible for 1988's record rate of aggravated assaults,
larceny and motor vehicle thefts, police said.
   ``I think we have to attribute a significant portion of all
these increases to crack,'' said Assistant Chief Raymond Kelly of
the department's Office of Management Analysis and Planning. ``It's
sweeping the country. It's been here since 1986, that's when the
figures started going up dramatically.''
   Officials had acknowledged in December that 1988 was the city's
most murderous year, topping the old record of 1,826 people set in
1981.
   The figures were released Friday.
   In 1988, 36.8 percent of all the homicides committed in the city
were drug related, Kelly said. ``And those are only the ones we are
definitely sure of. I'm sure there's more.''
   Homicides and non-negligent manslaughters topped the list of
crimes against people, increasing 13.4 percent in a year from 1,672
to 1,896.
   The only decline in crime came in the number of reported rapes,
which dropped 2.7 percent from 3,507 in 1987 to 3,412 in 1988.
   Department statisticians do not view that as a significant
decrease because ``generally speaking rape (cases) are
underreported,'' Kelly said.
</TEXT>
