<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Pakistan     03-25 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Pakistan,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Visit Shortened By `Satanic' Protest Fears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe will curtail a
visit to Pakistan for fear of fueling more Moslem protests over
Salman Rushdie's novel ``The Satanic Verses,'' British officials
said today.
   Plans for Howe to visit Afghan rebel leaders in the border town
of Peshawar have been scrapped, British officials said. He will
leave Sunday and remain in the capital, Islamabad, for two days
before going to India on a four-day visit.
   Howe added a stop in Madras, India, for the time that he was to
spend in Pakistan.
   ``There is no point in precipitating demonstrations (in
Pakistan),'' said a British official, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Howe is also due to stop for talks in Bahrain and Qatar en route
home.
   The foreign secretary is the most senior British official to
visit an Islamic country since Iran's Ayatollah Khomeini urged
Moslems to kill Rushdie, A native of Bombay and now a naturalized
British citizen. Many Moslems believe Rushdie's novel blasphemes
their religion.
   Khomeini's Feb. 14 death sentence prompted Britain and Iran to
cut diplomatic ties and chilled relations between Western and
Islamic countries. It also sent Rushdie into hiding.
   Moslems around the world have protested the novel. Some of the
most serious demonstrations have broken out in Pakistan and India,
where at least 19 people have died.
   Pakistani Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto, elected last year, has
accused Islamic fundamentalist opponents of using ``The Satanic
Verses'' issue as a cover to foment protests against her government.
   British officials say the visit to Pakistan was planned to
express support for Pakistan's recent democratic elections and for
the help Pakistan gives Afghan rebels.
   Howe has scheduled meetings with Ms. Bhutto in Islamabad and
with Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi in New Delhi.
</TEXT>
