<FIRST>r a PM-PhoneSex-AIDS     03-25 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Phone Sex-AIDS,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-AIDS Group Says Phone Sex `Safe'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to fix category code.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Phone-sex is safe sex, says a group that
promotes education about AIDS.
   ``In the age of AIDS, we need to make sure people have access to
forms of sexual expression which are completely safe,'' said
Benjamin Schatz of the National Gay Rights Advocates. ``We can't
allow conservative moralizing to take precedence over people's
lives.''
   Schatz's group has prepared a brief for the San Francisco AIDS
Foundation to be filed today with the U.S. Supreme Court.
   The court is reviewing a Federal Communications Commission
proposal to ban obscene or ``indecent'' commercial messages in
telephone calls on interstate lines or in the District of Columbia.
The calls are carried, for a fee, on numbers beginning with 900
prefixes.
   ``There is direct evidence that some people consciously use
`dial-a-porn' as a form of `safe sex' instead of engaging in sexual
contact involving the exchange of bodily fluids,'' the foundation
said in the papers.
   Records of the foundation's safe-sex workshops with homosexual
men reveal that participants named ``phone sex'' as a safe-sex
substitute in every recorded session.
   Schatz acknowledged that telephone sex does not always prevent
unsafe sex, and can even encourage it, but said the beneficial
effects outweigh any justification for a ban.
   ``It would be naive to say that this is something everybody
responds to in a socially responsible manner,'' he said. ``But
watching television can encourage unsafe sex, and that's no reason
to ban television.''
   The AIDS foundation, a non-profit educational and service
organization, argued in its Supreme Court brief that even obscene
phone messages that might otherwise be banned should be
constitutionally protected ``to the extent that they may divert
some individuals from life-threatening behavior.''
   ``Look at gay newspapers. You will find pages of ads for phone
sex lines, where years ago the ads would have been for
bathhouses,'' Schatz said Friday.
   The bathhouses, which have been shut down in San Francisco, were
viewed by health officials as major sources of transmission of
acquired immune deficiency syndrome in anonymous sexual contacts
between male homosexuals.
   AIDS, an affliction in which a virus attacks the body's immune
system, leaves victims susceptible to a wide variety of infections
and cancers. It is most often transmitted through sexual contact,
mostly between homosexual males.
   The brief argued that telephone sex not only serves as an
alternative to sexual contacts that can transmit AIDS, but also can
serve as a form of education to make safe sex more attractive.
   A study presented by U.S. public health researchers at a recent
international conference on AIDS in Stockholm found that ``sexually
explicit materials presenting safer sex behavior in an
affirmatively erotic manner was the most sucessful means of
motivating persons to change from high-risk to low- or no-risk
behavior,'' said the brief, signed by Schatz and lead attorney
Leonard Graff.
   Heterosexual as well as homosexual phone mssages should be
allowed because both groups can get AIDS from sexual contacts,
Schatz said.
   He said the foundation has no objection to regulation of
``dial-a-porn,'' such as blocking of the service by individual
households or restrictions on access to children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890325-0047 </DOCNO>
