<FIRST>r p PM-MayoralRadio     03-25 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mayoral Radio,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radio Stations Draw Black, White Audiences Together Before Mayoral
Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radio talk-show listeners from black and white
audiences are getting a chance to sound off together on special
programs aimed at easing racial tensions before Chicago's upcoming
mayoral election.
   WBBM-AM, a 50,000-watt station with a 75 percent white audience,
plans to join with WGCI-AM, a 5,000-watt station with a mostly
black audience, to broadcast a four-hour call-in talk show April 3,
on the eve of the election.
   ``Chicago is a very segregated city, and in many cases,
Chicago's radio stations are also segregated,'' said Chris Berry,
executive editor of WBBM, the all-news AM station that came up with
the idea.
   ``Race has been part of the campaign, in that we have had some
white and some black candidates running,'' he added Friday. ``It
looked to us as though voting would probably go along racial
lines.''
   The candidates are Democratic front-runner Richard M. Daley,
Republican Edward Vrdolyak, and Alderman Timothy Evans, a Democrat
running on a third-party slate. Daley and Vrdolyak are white. Evans
is black.
   Voting in the Feb. 28 mayoral primary was divided largely along
racial lines when Daley defeated Mayor Eugene Sawyer for the
Democratic nomination, becoming the first white candidate to defeat
a black incumbent mayor in a major U.S. city.
   Chicago's voting-age population is about 49 percent white, 42
percent black, 7 percent Hispanic and the remainder Asian and other
groups.
   After the WBBM-WGCI plan was announced two weeks ago, two other
stations joined for a similar program that aired Wednesday.
   Black-oriented WVON-AM teamed with public station WBEZ-FM for a
morning show on politics, social life and race, and agreed to do it
again the day after the election.
   ``I don't think we got into anything all that controversial,''
WBEZ announcer Ken Davis said of Wednesday's program. ``We were all
on our best behavior.''
   WBEZ's audience is 92 percent white and WVON's is 89 percent
black, according to the Chicago Tribune, and their combined show
reached an estimated 450,000 listeners.
   For the election-eve show produced by WBBM-WGCI, the candidates
themselves have been invited. Daley is expected to send a
representative, and Vrdolyak and Evans are expected to participate,
Berry said.
   Also, about 50 business and community leaders are being invited
to sit in as a studio audience and be potential participants, Berry
said.
   ``This is an opportunity for our listeners and their listeners
to talk with people they might not normally have the opportunity to
talk with and to discuss the issues facing this city,'' Berry added.
   Darlene Black, marketing director for WGCI, said: ``It's a
landmark thing to happen for two stations who are normally
competitors to come together for a common cause, but that's really
our main goal.''
   Ms. Black said the mayoral race ``has come down in some areas to
a black-white issue, and that's one of the things we're trying to
eliminate.''
   No estimate was available on WGCI's usual number of listeners,
but WBBM has a usual evening audience of 387,000 adults in the 18
counties surrounding Chicago, said spokeswoman Barbara DiGuido.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
