<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--ArtThefts     03-25 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Art Thefts,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>FBI Recovers $3.5 Million in Stolen Art Works</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI has recovered art objects worth $3.5
million that were from stolen from museums in five states.
   The pieces, ranging from a $2 million, 14th-century Chinese vase
to 16 antique pocketwatches worth $150,000, were displayed Friday.
   The 25 works were taken between Jan. 12 and Feb. 25 from museums
in Syracuse and Albany, N.Y., Boston, Baltimore, Detroit and
Columbus, Ohio.
   Most of the works were taken when the museums were open to the
public, said James Fox, head of the FBI's New York office.
   A five-count federal indictment charged George A. Athanasotos,
34, and Ronald Corteselli, 28, both of New York City, with
transporting the antiques across state lines and selling them.
   They pleaded innocent Thursday before U.S. Magistrate Kathleen
Roberts, who ordered them held without bail.
   Athanasotos also was charged with interstate transportation of a
$50,000 silver Tiffany pitcher stolen from the Detroit Institute of
Art on Jan. 12.
