<FIRST>r i PM-Egypt-Summit     03-25 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Egypt-Summit,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Egypt, Jordan, PLO Hold Talks on Middle East Strategy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISMAILIYA, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The heads of Egypt, Jordan and the PLO
met today to coordinate a Middle East peace strategy in preparation
for April and May talks in Washington between regional leaders and
President Bush.
   Today's meeting in this Suez Canal city brought together
Jordan's King Hussein, Palestine Liberation Organization leader
Yasser Arafat, and President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt for their
second summit in five months. They last met at Aqaba, Jordan, on
Oct. 22.
   The three are key players in the Arab drive to initiate peace
talks with Israel, primarily with U.S. help.
   Egyptian officials said the meeting came amid ``encouraging
developments'' that may augur well for the peace process.
   One development, said the officials who spoke on condition of
anonymity, was Wednesday's meeting in Tunisia between U.S. and PLO
representatives. No breakthrough was announced there, but the
parties began to discuss substantive issues for the first time
since the dialogue began last December.
   The officials also cited remarks by Bush in a Washington Times
interview Friday in which he praised the dialogue with the PLO and
said he would try to convince Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir
next month that ``something good might come'' from this.
   Shamir has refused to speak to the PLO, saying it is a terrorist
group.
   Bush is to meet in Washington with Mubarak on April 3, Shamir on
April 6 and King Hussein on May 2.
   The Egyptian officials said their summit was primarily intended
to build an Arab consensus on ways of advancing peace efforts. They
said the ideas would be taken up with Bush.
   They said a major aim is to persuade the United States and
Israel to back a proposed international conference as an umbrella
for Arab-Israeli negotiations. Inter-Arab consultations will
continue next week, with talks between Mubarak and King Fahd of
Saudi Arabia. Fahd is to arrive in Cairo on Monday for a four-day
official visit.
</TEXT>
