<HEAD>Iraq Bans Male Workers in Women's Health Clubs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has banned men from working
in women's health clubs ``in order to protect morality and women's
modesty,'' the ruling party's newspaper reported today.
   ``The practice of men helping women slim down contradicts our
educational course in building the new society and our traditional
values,'' the Baath party paper, Al-Thawra, quoted an Interior
Ministry spokesman as saying.
   The ministry, which ordered the ban, told women's clubs to fire
their male staff immediately, the report said.
   The government last year banned men from working in women's
hairdressing salons for similar reasons.
   Iraq is an Islamic country, but women are officially equal with
men and enjoy more social freedom than in many other Moslem nations.
