<FIRST>u i PM-Korea 1stLd-Writethru a0463 03-25 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0463,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radical Students Battle Riot Police in Seoul</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SEL1</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with pro-government rally. Pickup
5th graf pvs, ``Unite and...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radical students set several policemen
afire when they hurled firebombs and rocks in a riot today after
forming a new student alliance to try to oust President Roh
Tae-woo's embattled government.
   Police officials had no figures on injuries after 800 students
fought riot police at Yonsei University in Seoul. No arrests were
reported.
   A rival pro-government rally at Seoul Municipal Stadium today
attracted 40,000 people who urged Roh to suppress leftist groups,
according to Yonhap state news agency. The rally was organized by
conservative groups representing people who fled communist North
Korea after World War II.
   Most Koreans do not support radical students, who before the
riot denounced Roh and called for a joint struggle by students,
workers and farmers to topple the government. Student leaders
criticized the United States for backing Roh.
   ``Unite and overthrow the Roh Tae-woo regime,'' masked students
chanted as they pelted police with firebombs that exploded in
bursts of blazing gasoline and flying glass.
   Student representatives from 37 universities and colleges in
Seoul met at Yonsei to inaugurate the ``Student Struggle
Headquarters for the Overthrow of the Roh Regime.'' Similar groups
will be formed in other parts of the nation, student leaders said.
   About 4,000 riot police surrounded the sprawling campus in
eastern Seoul, firing tear gas and hurling rocks at the attacking
students. Police in armored vans fired salvos of choking tear gas,
and troopers made several charges to drive the students back during
about 90 minutes of fighting.
   During their rally, the radical leaders also denounced Roh for
his March 20 decision to postpone indefinitely a promised
referendum on his performance. Speakers said the action of Roh, an
elected president, proved he was not committed to genuine
democracy, and they called him a military dictator.
   Roh cited the threat of radical protests when he called off the
referendum.
   Speakers also demanded the immediate withdrawal of the 43,000
U.S. troops based in South Korea under a mutual defense treaty.
   The radical students and allied dissident groups have little
public support, and most South Koreans reject their militancy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890325-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-89 0947EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0468 03-25 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0468,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Soldiers Kill Two Palestinians, Arabs Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with 29 injured, more on collaborators.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers shot and killed two
Palestinian protesters today, and authorities discovered the bodies
of two Arabs suspected of collaborating with Israel, according to
Israeli and Arab reports.
   At least 29 Palestinians were wounded or injured in the
bloodiest confrontations this week with Israeli soldiers in the
occupied territories.
   The four deaths raised to 411 the number of Palestinians who
have been killed in the 15-month-old uprising against Israeli rule.
Eighteen Israelis also have died in the rebellion.
   Ashraf Abu Jazar, 17, died on the operating table at Nasser
Hospital in Khan Yunis after being shot in the abdomen during a
protest during which Palestinians threw stones at soldiers in
Rafah, the Arab reports said.
   The other Palestinian killed today was Adli Erbea, 22, who was
reported shot through the heart during a similar riot in Khan Yunis.
   The wounded included a 27-year-old woman struck by a bullet in
the right leg and a 12-year-old boy hit in the left thigh, Arab
hospital officials said.
   Also wounded seriously was an 18-year-old Palestinian from
Tarkumiya near the West Bank town of Hebron. He was rushed to Ahli
Hospital in Hebron with a plastic bullet wound in the chest, the
reports said.
   Witnesses said the clash in Tarkumiya came as more than 500
Palestinians marched to a cemetery carrying an outlawed Palestinian
flag and wreaths of carnations to commemorate the death a year ago
of two 18-year-old Palestinians in the town during a clash with
Israeli troops.
   Two protesters masked with kaffiyeh headdresses carried a large
white banner that said, ``We will avenge their deaths,'' and signed
in Arabic by the Unified National Leadership of the Uprising, the
witnesses said.
   The beaten and stabbed body of Jamal Abdel Hamid el Nadi was
found behind a girls' school in Gaza City's Rimal Quarter.
   Israel radio quoted Palestinian sources in Gaza as saying he was
slain because he was suspected of collaborating with Israel.
   The radio said the second dead man, Subhi Hamdan Elsoufi, 21,
whose body was discovered burned and beaten in Rafah, also was a
suspected collaborator.
   The army said both men were killed for criminal reasons and
declined to elaborate. Since the start of the uprising, Arabs have
killed more than 60 Palestinians they accuse of helping Israeli
authorities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
