<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-89 0949EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AssaultRifles     03-25 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Assault Rifles,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Customs Officials Ordered To Halt Previously OK'd Assault Rifle Shipments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Customs officials have been ordered to
halt previously approved shipments of more than 400,000
military-style assault weapons at the nation's borders, a newspaper
reported today.
   The Treasury Department's Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms had already approved the weapons shipments, but quickly
rescinded that approval Friday, the Los Angeles Times reported.
   The order follows the Bush administration's announcement earlier
this month that it was issuing a temporary ban on new permits
allowing the importation of five types of assault weapons into the
United States.
   Among those banned was the AK-47, the weapon used earlier this
year in a massacre of schoolchildren in Stockton, Calif.
   William T. Drake, a top official at ATF, acknowledged in an
interview with the Times that the move to ban previously approved
weapons shipments would be controversial. But he said an internal
audit detailing the vast extent of imports already authorized had
persuaded the agency to take the emergency action.
   When the moratorium on new permits was announced earlier this
month federal officials indicated they had no control over permits
already approved.
   However, Drake said his agency believes it was granted that
power under the 1968 Gun Control Act, which empowered the AFT to
grant licenses authorizing gun imports.
   ``What God giveth, God can taketh away,'' he said.
   The bureau declined to disclose how many weapons have been
approved for import, but an unidentified customs source told the
Times the number was 420,000.
   According to the ATF, 70,000 assault rifles have been imported
into the U.S. in the last three years.
</TEXT>
