<FIRST>u w PM-CableOut     03-25 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cable Out,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trans-Atlantic Phone Cable Out</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fiber-optic cable used by AT&amp;T for
trans-Atlantic phone calls failed early today, but service was
restored via satellite, the company reported.
   AT&amp;T spokesman Herb Linnen said the branch of the TAT-8 cable to
Britain failed about 12:50 a.m. EST.
   The cable splits into two branches as it approaches Europe, with
one going to Britain and the other to France. The French link
failed last Tuesday, and the traffic it normally carries had been
rerouted onto the British leg.
   Linnen said AT&amp;T phone service to Europe was disrupted in the
early morning hours, but was restored by mid-morning via the
Intelsat communications satellite.
   The fiber-optic cable can handle up to 40,000 phone calls
simultaneously, Linnen said. He said AT&amp;T knew the general location
of the failure but did not immediately know the reason.
   ``You have to send a cable ship out and they have to go out
where the fault is, and they just pull it up on board,'' he said.
</TEXT>
