<FIRST>r i PM-Yugoslavia 1stLd-Writethru a0476 03-25 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugoslavia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0476,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands of Ethnic Albanians Protest In Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Lead with 4 grafs to UPDATE with thousands demonstrating. Pickup
4th graf prv, ``Albanians are...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SLOBODAN LEKIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police used tear gas and truncheons
today to disperse thousands of stone-throwing ethnic Albanians
protesting constitutional changes that limit their autonomy in
southern Kosovo province, reports said.
   In the third straight day of demonstrations, up to 4,000
protesters clashed with police armed with machine guns and rifles
on the outskirts of Urosevac, 15 miles south of Pristina, the state
Tanjug news agency reported.
   Earlier today, about 300 Albanians hurled rocks at riot police
and troops gathered around army transport trucks in downtown
Urosevac.
   There were no immediate reports of arrests or injuries in either
protest.
   Albanians are protesting the provincial Parliament's approval
Thursday of constitutional amendments giving leaders from the
neighoring republic of Serbia more power in Kosovo.
   The amendments go into effect Tuesday after approval by the
Parliament in Serbia, the largest of Yugoslavia's six republics.
They give Serbia more power over police and judicial authorities
and allow the republic to pass amendments affecting Kosovo without
approval of the provincial parliament.
   Leaders of mainly Christian Serbia said they needed more control
over Kosovo to protect the Serbian minority from the mainly Moslem
ethnic Albanians, who make up 85 percent of Kosovo.
   The vote by the provincial legislature prompted protest rallies
Thursday and Friday by up to 10,000 people. The protests have
violated a ban on all public gatherings ordered last month.
   At least 10 policemen have been injured and more that 100
demonstrators arrested since protests began Thursday. Most arrested
protesters were immediately convicted of ``petty crime'' and
sentenced to between 30 and 60 days in jail, the government's
Tanjug news agency said.
   Twenty-five ethnic Albanian miners and 40 factory workers were
also sentenced to 60 days in prison for defying a recently
introduced ``compulsory work order'' to prevent a proposed general
strike, the news agency said.
</TEXT>
