<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Iran-Drugs     03-25 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Iran-Drugs,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Addicts Sent To Labor Camps</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities rounded up 200 drug addicts
in the Iranian capital Saturday and said the addicts will be sent
to labor camps in southeast Iran, state-run Tehran radio reported.
   The radio, monitored in Nicosia, quoted an unidentified police
official as saying the addicts will build barricades in
Sistan-Baluchistan province intended to prevent narcotics smugglers
from entering Iran.
   The addicts will be kept in the camps from six months to a year
and will be compensated for their labor, the official was quoted as
saying. He gave no details.
   More than 350 drug smugglers have been executed and several
thousand addicts rounded up under a new anti-narcotics law that
took effect Jan. 21.
   The new law carries the death sentence for possession of even
small quantities of drugs and gives addicts six months to kick the
habit or face jail terms.
   Iran's official media estimate there are 1 million drug addicts
in Iran, which has a population of 50 million. Unofficial estimates
put the figure at 2 million.
</TEXT>
