<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-89 1055EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Egypt-Palestinian Bjt   03-25 0755</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egypt-Palestinian, Bjt,0780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian Children's Books Offer Subtle Political Themes</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEJLA SAMMAKIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tales to enchant children with titles such
as ``The White Pigeon'' or ``Locusts in The City'' line the shelves
of Middle Eastern classrooms and homes.
   Behind their shiny covers and bright pictures lie subtle
messages of nationhood, homeland and a people's yearning _ the
messages of the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   These books and others published by Dar Al-Fata Al-Arabi, the
Arab Youth House, repeatedly drive home the proclaimed PLO
philosophy on what young Palestinians should be taught: ``Hope,
ambition and persistence for independence ... during the struggle
against Zionism and imperialism.''
   The chairman of the Cairo-based publishing house, Nabil Shaath,
is an aide to PLO chief Yasser Arafat and a member of the Palestine
National Council. He and 19 other wealthy Palestinians started Dar
Al-Fata in 1974 with $100,000.
   But Hasna Mekdashi, the company's executive manager, denies the
organization still influences Dar Al-Fata. The house was guided by
the PLO's educational planning department at first, she said, but
it is now independent. ``Our themes are really about universal
values,'' Mrs. Mekdashi said, noting that many of the little books
have been translated into English and other languages.
   Nevertheless, the message remains.
   In ``The White Pigeon'' by Syrian writer Zakaria Tamer, Little
Pigeon ventures out of the nest to discover the world, gets lost
but eventually makes her way home.
   After chiding her daughter for leaving, Mama Pigeon recalls that
she did the same thing as a chick but that her love of home guided
her back. She marvels, in a commentary on the Palestinian diaspora:
``All those who are lost and far away from their homes will be
guided back to them by their love for their homes.''
   And the message changes with PLO policy shifts.
   Although the PLO recently has taken a conciliatory posture in
its conflict with Israel and says it wants a political solution to
the Middle East crisis, early Dar Al-Fata publications had a
militant flavor to them.
   ``The Home,'' a brightly colored 1974 pamphlet, depicts the
dwellings of birds, animals and fish.
   Then, beside a picture of a tank with a Star of David on its
side, it says the residence of the Palestinian is occupied by the
enemy. Next is a rifle dominating an orange-colored page, and
author Tamer concludes: ``How will the Palestinian regain his home?
With arms alone.''
   The publication was distributed at the United Nations when
Arafat spoke to the General Assembly in 1975, Mrs. Mekdashi said.
   Shaath said in an interview that the booklet was written 15
years ago but said if it were written today, ``We would say by arms
and persuasion.''
   He laughed. ``Now I would say more persuasion than arms.''
   Shaath planned Dar Al-Fata soon after a dispute between
Palestinians in Jordan and King Hussein deteriorated into war in
September 1970. Hussein's army drove out Arafat and the PLO's
guerrilla forces.
   Soon, the publishing house had another experience with Arab
schisms. It had to move its headquarters from Beirut to Cairo in
1976 when civil war broke out, although its main printing
facilities remain in the battered Lebanese capital.
   Of the house's 260 books and posters, 12 are translated into
English, four into Swedish and a few into French, Spanish and
German. The translated works serve mainly ethnic Arab communities
in the United States, Britain, France and Australia, giving them a
taste of their ancestors' culture.
   The publishing house has not shirked from criticizing Arab
divisions and rhetoric.
   Plant-devouring insects swarm into a town in ``Locusts in the
City.'' Instead of attending to the business of eliminating the
pests, residents spend their time talking about the problem and
making eloquent speeches critical of the insects. The book
concludes: ``When the locusts occupied the city, they did not leave
it. They are still eating the grass, the ears of wheat and the
leaves of the trees.''
   In ``The House of White Paper,'' Dar Al-Fata shows Palestinian
children the benefits of cooperation. Five pencils draw a house in
an idyllic setting, with a dog, cat and crows, but a donkey
intrudes and takes over the house. Pencils, paper, animals and
crows confer and decide to attack.
   ``The pencils rained down blows on the donkey, the cat bit the
donkey, the dog bit the donkey, and the crows pecked at the
donkey,'' the book says.
   ``Though (the donkey) brayed and kicked out violently, he was
forced after a while to flee.''
</TEXT>
