<FIRST>r a AM-TrainDeath     03-25 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Train Death,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen-ager Charged With Throwing Cousin Off Train</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERSEY CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was arrested Saturday after he
allegedly pushed his cousin through the window of a moving train
while they were on their way to work, police said.
   Ryan Smith, 18, of Jersey City, was pronounced dead at St.
Mary's Hospital in Hoboken at 11:50 p.m. Friday, about an hour
after he was rescued from the tracks, officials said.
   His cousin, Eddie Lee Warren, 20, who lived in the same
apartment building as Smith, was charged with manslaughter, said
Port Authority police Lt. James McGovern.
   Smith, Warren and three other men boarded the Manhattan-bound
train in Jersey City and were on their way to work in Weehawken,
where they were employed by Wells Fargo Guard Service, McGovern
said.
   ``There was some horseplay and some fooling around and some
violent contact on the train,'' he said. ``As a result of that, the
victim was ejected'' through a window which had fallen out of its
frame.
   The train was traveling at 12 mph when an emergency brake was
pulled. Passengers brought Smith back onto the train, which took
him to the Hoboken station where he was met by an ambulance. The
train apparently did not run over him, McGovern said.
   Smith's only visible injury was a cut on his forehead and the
cause of death was unknown, said Ed Capparucci, a hospital
spokesman. An autopsy was planned.
</TEXT>
