<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-89 1101EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Nepal-India     03-25 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nepal-India,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>India Terminates Trade Treaties With Nepal, Officials Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   India has ended trade and transit
agreements with Nepal despite a proposal by the Himalayan kingdom
for negotiations on new treaties, Nepalese officials say.
   The Indo-Nepalese trade treaty expired a year ago and India
terminated its provisions Thursday night, according to a notice
given Nepalese officials by the Indian government.
   A separate transit agreement expired Thursday even though
Nepalese authorities had asked India to continue adhering to its
provisions until a new arrangement was signed, a spokesman of
Nepal's Foreign Office said Friday.
   Nepal also has proposed immediate negotiations on a new treaty.
   But India had been insisting that both the trade and transit
treaties be linked in a single new treaty, the official said.
   Nepal's foreign minister, Shailendra Kumar Upadhyaya, was to
travel to New Delhi on Sunday for talks on resolving the matter.
   Nepalese officials said that, according to the Indian
government's notice, 13 of the 15 customs check points along the
nations' 1,090-mile border have been closed because of the
treaties' termination.
   The officials also said that under the transit treaty, India had
provided free access for the overland transportation of goods
imported and exported by Nepal. Now, they said, the Indian
government has imposed customs duty on all goods exported to India
from Nepal.
   The officials said Nepal had not changed its customs rates for
trade with India.
</TEXT>
