<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--India-Computer     03-25 0111</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--India-Computer,0114</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gandhi Dedicates U.S.-Made Supercomputer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi on Saturday
dedicated the country's first supercomputer, which will be used to
provide farmers with more precise weather forecasts.
   The Cray supercomputer, obtained from the United States for $500
million, has been installed at the National Center for Medium-Range
Weather Forecasting.
   Gandhi thanked former President Ronald Reagan for his interest
in the project and helping India get its first supercomputer.
   The government says the Cray XMP-14 will be used to provide
weather forecasts three to 10 days in advance, to prepare
advisories and to study the impact of weather and climate on pests
and diseases.
</TEXT>
