<FIRST>r i PM-Ireland-Gorbachev     03-25 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ireland-Gorbachev,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Haughey Likely To Offer Ireland As Summit Venue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Charles Haughey is likely
to offer Ireland as a venue for the next superpower summit when he
meets Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev on April 2, government
sources said today.
   The first meeting between the two leaders, which Gorbachev
requested, will be held at Shannon International Airport in western
Ireland during a refueling stop on the Soviet president's flight to
Cuba.
   Haughey met with President Bush during a St. Patrick's Day visit
to Washington, and the announcement of Gorbachev's visit to Dublin
fueled speculation Haughey might offer Ireland for the first
Bush-Gorbachev summit.
   Asked to comment on the possibility, a government source, who
spoke on condition of anonymity, said: ``An offer to use Ireland is
in the cards.''
   Last year, Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze was asked
during a visit to Ireland about the possibility of holding a summit
in Ireland. He replied that Ireland, because of its military
neutrality, would be a very ``receptive location'' if it were
offered.
   Haughey will assume the rotating presidency of the 12-nation
European Economic Community in January. Sources said that may be
the reason Gorbachev requested a meeting with the Irish leader.
   Gorbachev has been cultivating closer ties with Western Europe.
He and his wife, Raisa, will visit Britain from April 5-7 on their
way home from Cuba. He is also scheduled to visit West Germany in
mid-June and France July 4-6.
   Haughey said in a statement his brief talks with Gorbachev would
focus on international and bilateral issues including the
development of the ``excellent relationship between Ireland and the
Soviet Union.''
   Gorbachev's stopover at Shannon will be the first official visit
to Ireland by a Soviet leader, said the Department of Foreign
Affairs.
</TEXT>
