<FIRST>u i PM-SovietElection 4thLd-Writethru   03-25 0745</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Election, 4th Ld-Writethru,a0478,0762</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Rally For Yeltsin On Eve Of Soviet Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY6</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to RECAST lede and UPDATE with rally peaceful.
Pickup 4th graf pvs, ``The demonstrators...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN IAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people attended a rally today for
Boris N. Yeltsin, the maverick Communist Party member who has
criticized the privileges of the party's elite in his campaign for
a seat on the new congress.
   Soviets vote Sunday to fill 1,500 seats in the 2,250-member
Congress of People's Deputies, a new chamber created last year in
broad electoral reforms championed by President Mikhail Gorbachev.
It will be the first contested election in the Soviet Union in more
than 70 years.
   About 10,000 people, chanting slogans and waving posters,
attended the peaceful, outdoor rally today in a large parking lot
next to Lenin Stadium.
   The demonstrators, echoing a central theme of Yeltsin's election
campaign, demanded an end to privileges for the Communist Party
elite, such as special food stores and chauffeured limousines.
   ``Do away with special privileges for politicians and
bureaucrats,'' said a typical placard that one demonstrator held
aloft on a ski pole. ``Servants of the people should have to stand
in line,'' said another.
   About 5,000 people streamed into the parking lot under partly
cloudy skies before the noon rally, and the crowd swelled to more
than 10,000 an hour later, forcing police to hold people back from
a roped off area.
   Hundreds of police lined the entrance to the parking lot outside
of the former Olympic stadium, and scores of officers waited in
dozens of buses parked nearby. Around a bend in the road, hidden by
trees, 50 military trucks packed with soldiers stood by in the
event the rally got out of control.
   ``This is what it must have been like in 1917,'' said a Yeltsin
supporter, referring to the year of the communist revolution. ``I
have not seen anything like it in my lifetime.''
   Rally organizers, from three Moscow political action groups,
obtained permission for the three-hour rally after convincing
authorities it would be better than having an illegal demonstration
such as the one Sunday in downtown Moscow in which thousands of
Yeltsin supporters gathered and marched.
   Yeltsin is running against Yevgeny Brakov, director of the ZIL
auto factory that supplies limousines for the Kremlin leadership,
for the right to represent all of Moscow in the new congress.
   The 58-year-old Yelstin was ousted as head of the Moscow
Communist Party Gorbachev in November 1987. Yeltsin and his
supporters have accused the party of trying to discredit him with
critical articles in the official media.
   Brakov, 51, is running a low-key campaign on the issue of ending
chronic Soviet food shortages. ``I am for a speedy decision on the
food problem, development of food and processing industries,'' he
said in an article written for the newspaper Economic Gazette.
   Yeltsin supporters at the rally said they believed their
candidate, who did not appear at the rally, would win the votes of
5 million of Moscow's 6.5 million eligible voters.
   About 190 million of the 280 million Soviets are eligible to
vote Sunday, according to the Central Election Commission. Soviets
over 18 years old are eligible to cast ballots, except those
certified as insane. Voting is not mandatory, and ballots will be
secret, the official news agency Tass said.
   Voting precincts ranging in size from 20 to 3,000 people will be
set up throughout the Soviet Union, including at polar research and
mountain stations as well as on navy ships at sea, Tass said today.
   The 750 seats in the new assembly that will not be contested in
the election were filled by the Communist Party and other
officially sanctioned groups ranging from labor unions to an
association of stamp collectors.
   More than 80 percent of the candidates for the 1,500 seats that
are up for grabs in the election are party members.
   In a quarter of Sunday's races, only one candidate is running.
   The party has dominated the selection of candidates and will, if
only by mathematics, also dominate the assembly after Sunday's
balloting.
   Moreover, the new chamber will meet just once a year to pick a
working legislature. Thus, the party should be able to stack the
legislature with its own members if it so chooses.
   Nevertheless, the campaign has brought competition and public
debate of a kind almost impossible to imagine in the pre-Gorbachev,
pre-perestroika era.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
