<DOCNO> AP890325-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-89 1236EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China     03-25 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China,0588</SECOND>
<HEAD>Austerity Is Great, But Not In My Backyard</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>By JOHN POMFRET</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Li Peng's call last week for huge
spending cuts to slow the overheated economy has angered local
officials, highlighting centuries-old tension between China's
central government and its unruly provinces.
   Beijing demands austerity. That's fine, the provinces say, but
not at their expense.
   China's local governments have taken swipes at Li's plan to slow
exaggerated industrial growth and high inflation through
recentralization of the economy under a government less generous
with handouts.
   First to speak out was the governor of Guangdong, China's most
prosperous province, located next to Hong Kong, about 1,200 miles
from Beijing.
   ``Guangdong should be an exception,'' Ye Xuanping Thursday told
delegates to the National People's Congress, China's legislature.
``We are a special province and we should be treated differently.''
   Next came Chen Xitong, mayor of the capital, Beijing, which is
treated as a province by the Chinese government.
   ``Beijing must be protected, must be protected,'' Chen boomed
during a session with delegates from Beijing. ``After all, China
only has one capital.''
   Officials from Guizhou, Qinghai and Yunnan, all poorer
provinces, followed suit.
   ``Look at all these big buildings in Beijing,'' said one
delegate from Yunnan, a rural province in China's mountainous
southwest. ``Stop one of those hotels and you'd help thousands of
my people in the countryside.''
   Luo Pingyi, a delegate from Guizhou in the south, said austerity
measures ``should not be applied to us who are falling behind.''
   Local governments have clashed with China's central government
since the Communist revolution in 1949, and for centuries before.
   One dynasty, the Sung, actually abolished provinces in the 10th
century and put all officials under the emperor's direct control.
The communist government regularly rotates its governors to avoid
the development of independent power bases.
   On Monday, Premier Li opened China's annual legislative session
with a call for belt-tightening and thrift.
   China's overheated industrial sector grew 17 percent last year.
Inflation is running at 36 percent, the highest since the Communist
victory in 1949.
   Li said local governments must abandon selfishness.
   ``All localities, departments and units should take the
interests of the whole into account and firmly subordinate their
local interests,'' Li said.
   A day later, Vice-premier Yao Yilin and Minister of Finance Wang
Bingqian weighed in with some specifics: increased taxes and cuts
in funding for enterprises operating outside the centralized state
plan, greater central control of loans, a stronger national bank.
   In addition, provinces and cities, which recently gained the
right to trade with and borrow money from foreign countries, saw
those rights diminished. Poorer provinces were told to expect less
help.
   But many provinces aren't so sure they want the recentralization
of the country's economy.
   Richer provinces benefited from the recent trend toward
decentralizing economic decision-making and the accompanying new
political power.
   Counties got rich opening mines and starting little factories.
Cities prospered, cutting deals with foreign countries and trading
among themselves.
   Poorer provinces still need state subsidies and aid, and their
delegates said austerity will have little effect on prosperous
coastal provinces.
   ``To the coastal areas, the retrenchment is like taking a knife
to the tale of an ox,'' said Huanjue Cailang, a delegate from
impoverished Qinghai. ``But to us poor districts, it's like hitting
him on the head with a brick.''
</TEXT>
