<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-89 1241EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w BC-Bush-Text     03-25 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Bush-Text,390</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of a statement from President
Bush issued by the White House on Saturday in honor of the 1979
Middle East peace agreement:
   Ten years ago, representatives of Egypt and Israel met here in
the presence of American witnesses to sign a treaty that
transformed the political map of the Middle East. Of course, I
speak of the peace agreement ending over 30 years of war between
Egypt and Israel.
   The treaty was the product of vision, statesmanship, courage and
persistence on the part of all the participants. Anwar Sadat's
historic trip to Jerusalem illustrated dramatically how one man
could raise his nation above the hostility and isolation the Arab
states showed Israel for over three decades. Menachem Begin's
response demonstrated the courage to overcome fears and obstacles
in pursuit of a larger goal. And the American team pursued every
lead toward peace and contributed critically to the process begun
by previous administrations.
   Recognizing the historic achievement of 10 years ago, however,
turns our minds toward the still more daunting challenges ahead. If
we wish truly to honor those whose bravery and hard work made
possible the peace treaty we need to complete the work they began.
We must commit ourselves as Anwar Sadat and Menachem Begin did to
fresh thinking.
   The Middle East today remains a dangerous and volatile area.
Deep seated hostilities and legitimate security concerns frustrate
efforts to expand the peace. And yet there are hopeful signs. The
desire to find a peaceful settlement is increasingly widespread.
There is also a growing understanding that a settlement can be
reached which both satisfies Israel's security needs and addresses
the legitimate political rights of the Palestinians. What worked in
the Egypt-Israel peace treaty _ negotiations based on U.S. Security
Council resolutions 242 and 338 _ can work as the basis for a wider
lasting peace.
   This administration is committed to this goal. We must be
patient but we must never stop trying. The search for peace will
continue to animate our discussions with good friends from Egypt,
Isarel and other middle eastern countries as they visit here or as
we visit there. The best way to do honor to those who gave us the
treaty of peace with Israel and Egypt would be to bring peace to
the entire Middle East.
</TEXT>
