<FIRST>r a AM-FatherSlain     03-25 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Father Slain,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>13-Year-Old Daughter Implicated In Father's Killing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANTECA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 13-year-old girl let two boyfriends
into her home so they could kill her father, who was strangled,
stabbed and beaten on the head with a fireplace poker, police said.
   Michelle Say was taken into custody Friday in connection with
Tuesday's death of Ronnie Edward Say, 47. Officers already had
arrested two boys who Say reportedly had not wanted around his
daughter.
   Ironically, Say, who recently was divorced, had moved to Manteca
with his daughter in hopes of avoiding urban crime in the San
Francisco Bay area 75 miles west.
   Witnesses told investigators that Michelle let the boys into her
home before she went to school, where she was a seventh grade
student.
   ``She knew when she left the house that they were going to kill
him,'' Capt. Charles Halford said.
   A girlfriend reported that the two boys met her and Michelle in
a park Tuesday evening and made statements about the slaying.
Michelle then returned home and found her father's body in a pool
of blood in the bathroom.
   ``What is unusual about this one is the age of the defendants
and the brutality of the crime,'' Halford said. ``He was beaten
repeatedly with fireplace tools. He was strangled, stabbed and
beaten. The autopsy shows he could have died from all three.''
   Berto Talaveras, 15, and his cousin, Juan Valdez, 13, were
charged with attacking Say when he returned home from work. A
Juvenile Court judge officially made their names public despite
their ages because the names already had been published in two
newspapers.
   Despite their youth, both boys outweighed Say. State Department
of Motor Vehicles records describe the victim as 5-foot-3, 125
pounds. Police said the boys weighed between 160 and 170 pounds
each.
   Judge Duane Martin also allowed reporters and news photographers
into Juvenile Court for Friday's arraignment of Talaveras and
Valdez, an unusual action because most Juvenile Court proceedings
are kept secret. Martin said he had the legal discretion under
California law to open the proceedings to the public because of the
crime's ``heinous nature.''
   Separate public defenders were appointed to represent each boy,
and the arraignment was continued until April 13. The defendants
cannot be tried as adults because they are under 16, so the maximum
penalty they can face is sentencing to the California Youth
Authority until age 25, the judge said.
   Max Valdez, brother of defendant Juan Valdez, was quoted in the
Modesto Bee as implicating Michelle Say, or Micke as he called her.
   ``Micke was in on it,'' Max Valdez told the newspaper. ``Micke
always hated her father, She wanted him dead.''
   The newspaper said Michelle dated Juan Valdez after the Says
moved to Manteca last September and was dating Talaveras at the
time of her father's death.
   Talaveras was expelled from Manteca High School last year, said
district spokesman William Whiteside; he refused to reveal the
reason.
</TEXT>
