<FIRST>r i AM-Israel     03-25 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Palestinians Killed, 35 Wounded or Injured in Fighting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Palestinians were killed Saturday and 35
others were injured in some of the bloodiest outbreaks of
anti-Israeli violence in the occupied territories, according to
Arab and Israeli reports.
   The army confirmed four people were dead and nine wounded.
   It said two Palestinians were killed in clashes with soldiers in
the occupied Gaza Strip. The bodies of two others found in Gaza
were apparently killed after being suspected of collaborating with
Israel, Arab reports and Israeli media said.
   The four deaths raised to 411 the number of Palestinians who
have been killed in the 15-month-old uprising against Israeli rule,
including 60 suspected Arab collaborators. Eighteen Israelis also
have died.
   Also Saturday, about 60 Israeli peace activists, including three
rabbis, traveled to the West Bank town of Beit Sahour, where they
discussed peace with dozens of Palestinians over plates of chicken
and salad, witnesses said.
   The activists of the ``Peace Now'' movement said they sought to
prove ``dialogue between Israelis and Palestinians is possible when
the government and the army do not interfere.''
   The body of one alleged collaborator, Jamel Abdel Hamid Nadi,
was found Saturday behind a school in Gaza City's Rimal Quarter
with multiple stab wounds and signs of beatings, Arab reports said.
   The reports said graffiti reportedly scribbled on a wall near
Nadi's home and signed by the Islamic Fundamentalist ``Hamas'' or
Zeal movement, claimed the group had killed him for cooperating
with the Israelis.
   The other body was discovered in Rafah in southern Gaza and was
identified as Subhi Hamdan Elsoufi, 21. Arab reports said Elsoufi
was killed as a collaborator.
   Israel's television and radio also said both men found slain
were killed on suspicion of collaborating with Israel.
   But the army denied either were collaborators and said that an
investigation into their deaths showed ``the men were killed as a
result of an internal feud of a criminal nature,'' in a statement
handed to journalists.
   The two other deaths were in Rafah and Khan Yunis in the Gaza
Strip, where soldiers opened fire on stone-throwing protesters,
fatally wounding Ashraf Abu Jazar, 17, in the abdomen and Adli
Erbea, 22, in the heart, Arab reports said.
   It was the highest daily casualty toll in the rebellion for
about three months. Twelve Palestinians and one Israeli have been
killed in the past week.
   Eighteen Palestinians suffered gunshot wounds during protests in
Gaza Saturday, among them an 11-year-old girl and two 12-year-old
boys.
   Seventeen were injured by rubber bullets in the West Bank, Arab
reports said.
   The army confirmed only nine of the wounded in clashes in the
West bank towns of Nablus and Tarkumiya.
   The clash in Tarkumiya came as more than 500 Palestinians
marched to a cemetery carrying an outlawed Palestinian flag and
wreaths of carnations to commemorate the death a year ago of two
18-year-old Palestinians in the town during a clash with Israeli
troops.
   Two protesters carried a large white banner that said, ``We will
avenge their deaths,'' and signed in Arabic by the PLO-led Unified
National Leadership of the Uprising, the witnesses said.
</TEXT>
