<FIRST>r i AM-Vietnam-USMIAs     03-25 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vietnam-US MIAs,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnamese, U.S. Officials Discuss MIA Issue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Vietnamese technical experts
have discussed plans for further joint investigations to account
for Americans listed as missing in action in the Vietnam War, the
U.S. team said Saturday.
   A statement from the team leader, Lt. Col. Joe Harvey, said the
two sides held the regular talks in Vietnam's capital, Hanoi, from
Tuesday to Friday.
   It said the talks were productive and ``concentrated on plans
for moving forward with joint investigations of discrepancy cases.''
   These are cases on which the United States says Vietnamese
authorities should have information, such as American pilots who
were captured but failed to emerge from prisoner of war camps.
   The statement said they also discussed reports in which
Americans were supposedly sighted in Vietnam after the war and
future excavations of warplane crash sites to search for human
remains.
   The U.S. team gave the Vietnamese additional information for
their unilateral investigations, the statement said.
   Harvey is commander of the U.S. Joint Casualty Resolution
Center, the Honolulu-based military unit entrusted with resolving
the fates of 2,371 Americans who never returned from the war in
Indochina, which ended with Communist victories in 1975. Of those,
1,737 are reported missing in Vietnam, 545 in Laos, 83 in Cambodia
and six in China.
   In Vietnam, work on the issue has accelerated since an August
1987 agreement between a U.S. presidential envoy, retired Gen. John
W. Vessey, and Vietnam's foreign minister, Nguyen Co Thach.
   The two sides since have conducted four joint investigations on
some of the 70 discrepancy cases the United States considers top
priority.
   A U.S. military team flew to southern Laos on March 18 for a
joint excavation of a crash site. Laos had delayed that project for
two weeks in a show of displeasure over U.S. State Department
charges it was not cooperating with U.S. narcotics suppression
efforts.
</TEXT>
