<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-89 1600EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Arson     03-25 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Arson,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Suspect Animal Rights Activists In Arson Fires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDINBURGH, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arsonists set fires that extensively
damaged two animal research laboratories in the Edinburgh area on
Saturday, authorities said, and four firefighters were injured
while battling the blazes.
   Police sent warnings to other animal research establishments in
Scotland to be on alert for possible arson attacks.
   ``We don't know if it was animal rights people but we suspect
them,'' said Assistant Divisional Fire Officer David Mercer. ``The
investigation has been handed over to the police.''
   Acting Fire Chief Peter Scott, who was at both fires, condemned
those responsible for risking the lives of firefighters. ``If
anyone had wanted to design a trap for firefighters they could not
have done better. I'm livid,'' he said.
   Flames leaped up to 20 feet into the air from the the Edinburgh
University animal research unit near Penicuik, 10 miles south of
Edinburgh.
   Fire officials said empty gasoline cans were found later in the
corridors of the unit at Macaulay House.
   Two firefighters were injured as they battled to prevent flames
from reaching dangerous chemicals, gas cylinders and a small
radioactive source, firefighters said. One suffered smoke
inhalation and the chemical burns.
   Dr. Jeff Maxwell, director of the unit, said animals including
sheep, cows and deer were in an adjacent building, which was not
damaged.
   Shortly after the blaze was brought under control, a second fire
was reported at the Agricultural Research Council's poultry
breeding research station at Roslin, two miles away. Firemen said
methylated spirits and soaked rags were found outside the center.
   Two firfighters evacuating the building were cut by flying glass
when there was an explosion, fire officials said.
   John Hearn, deputy secretary of the Agricultural and Food
Research Council, which runs the poultry unit, said:
   ``Much of the world's leading research in these laboratories is
designed to improve animal health and welfare.
   ``Those responsible for such attacks have no regard for either
animals or humans. They show dangerous ignorance and stupidity.''
   The Scottish agriculture minister, Lord Sanderson, visited the
scene of the university fire and described it as a ``major tragedy
involving the loss of much valuable scientific research.''
   Animal rights activists have targeted research facilities in
their campaign to halt what they claim is cruelty to animals used
in laboratory experiments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
