<FIRST>r i AM-BoatPeople     03-25 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boat People,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Find Two Bodies, Apparently of Boat People Killed in Collision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have found bodies of two
women believed to be Vietnamese refugees who drowned after their
boat sank near a Japanese tanker, local newspapers reported
Saturday.
   The bodies were washed ashore on Perhentian Kechil island, 210
miles northeast of Kuala Lumpur, the daily New Straits Times said
in a report quoting police in the area.
   Some of the 35 refugees who survived the March 8 sinking said
130 people died when the boat capsized in the South China Sea as
the tanker Nissei-Maru approached to help it.
   The refugees said the tanker collided with the boat, but tanker
captain Yasuo Kawamura said strong waves created by the tanker's
propeller capsized their boat. Kawamura said strong ocean currents
and winds hampered rescue efforts and that three nearby shipos
ignored his mayday calls for help.
   Malaysian police said the two bodies found Friday were taken to
the mortuary of a government hospital.
   On Monday, the body of another woman believed to be a refugee
who died in the March 8 tragedy was found on Perhentian Kechil,
police said.
   The sinking was reported by fishermen who said they saw several
bodies floating in the sea near the island. It was not reported in
Japan until Monday, when survivors arrived in Yokohama.
   Japan's Maritime Safety Agency is investigating the accident,
which is the latest in a series involving the growing number of
Vietnamese fleeing political repression and economic hardship in
their homeland.
   The refugees, known as boat people, risk piracy and disaster in
hopes of achieving asylum in other countries.
   
   Malaysia gives temporary asylum to refugees looking to resettle
in the West. About 16,500 boat people live in Malaysian refugee
camps.
</TEXT>
