<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     03-25 0723</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0753</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Given the chance to put a man behind bars for
shoplifting, an athletic footwear store owner instead decided to
put the alleged robber in his shoes.
   Francis Y. Kim, owner of Family Shoeport, not only forgave the
27-year-old man, but offered him a job, gave him a pair of socks to
go with the stolen shoes and drove him home from the police station.
   ``I didn't think he would want to make a mess out of his life
for one pair of shoes,'' Kim said.
   ``He said he needed them so I give him a chance to earn them,''
Kim said. ``If he went to jail, it wouldn't do any good. He'd just
come out and steal more.''
   Neither Kim nor police disclosed the suspect's name.
   ``We've had people drop charges before ... but this is the first
time I've had a complainant drop charges and hire the suspect just
like that,'' said police detective Mike Tanaka.
   According to police, Kim tackled the suspect as he fled his
store Thursday wearing a pair of $105 prestige-brand basketball
shoes.
   Kim later visited the man in jail.
   ``He had no job but he really liked the shoes. I told him jail
would worsen his life, and you come out and do something more
ridiculous,'' Kim said. ``If you can promise me you'll try, I'll
give a chance.''
   ``This is a better way for him, for me and for society,'' Kim
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GULF BREEZE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colossus, reputed to be the largest
gorilla in captivity, apparently isn't considered much of a simian
hunk by his would-be mate Muke.
   The female was brought to The Zoo near this Pensacola suburb
here on breeding loan from the St. Louis Zoo, but the couple hasn't
quite clicked, said Pat Quinn, director of The Zoo.
   ``They have shown no signs of mating,'' Quinn said recently.
``She has shown no sign of presenting herself and I'm not sure yet
he knows what to do.''
   Muke _ pronounced Moo-key _ is the only other gorilla that
Colossus has seen since he was an infant 20 years earlier.
   Otherwise, the socialization of Colossus, who had lived in
solitude at a zoo in New Hampshire for most of his life, has gone
well, Quinn said. He is no longer abusive to Muke although he does
exert his dominance and herd her around, which Quinn said is normal
for a gorilla.
   But there has been no courting in the courtyard.
   ``Gorillas have to like each other to breed,'' Quinn said.
``Maybe he doesn't think she's pretty, although I think she is
beautiful. And maybe she doesn't care for him too much.''
   Colossus, believed to be the biggest gorilla in captivity at
more than 550 pounds, is considered a good breeding candidate
because he was captured in the wild as a baby and would bring some
new genes into the world's captive gorilla population. Quinn said
he may seek other mates for the animal.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MILLERSVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jean MacNemar Cannon arrived in the
world on the shoulder of the Baltimore Washington Parkway while a
parade of cars sped by in heavy rush hour traffic.
   Jean just wouldn't wait until her parents could get to a
Baltimore hospital.
   ``It was a thrill a minute,'' her mother, Barbara MacNemar, said
Friday, recalling the race to Baltimore from their Millersville
home nine days earlier. ``She plunked herself out a little earlier
than expected.''
   With Ms. MacNemar's husband, Shelton Cannon, acting as deliverer
and driver, the 8-pound, 8-ounce girl was born in the family's
Volvo.
   When Ms. MacNemar went into labor early March 15, the couple
took their time leaving for the hospital because their first child
was born after 26 hours of labor, Cannon said.
   But just before they reached the Baltimore Beltway, Ms. MacNemar
said Jean was about to be born. Cannon didn't believe her at first.
   ``I'm trying to tell her, `No, no, breathe through it,''' he
said. But the baby was born without complications a few minutes
later.
   Nobody stopped to help, and the couple doubts anyone was aware
of the roadside birth. ``We weren't stopped very long,'' Ms.
MacNemar said. ``Traffic was just whizzing by.''
   Cannon drove mother and child to University Hospital in
Baltimore, where they stayed overnight before being released.
</TEXT>
