<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-89 1645EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-ArabLeague     03-25 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arab League,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jordan, Iraq, North Yemen Threaten To Boycott Arab League</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISMAILIYA, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jordan's King Hussein said on Saturday
that his country, Iraq and North Yemen will boycott future Arab
summits unless Egypt regains its Arab League seat.
   Hussein linked his surprise disclosure of a boycott threat to
calls for an extraordinary league summit to forge unified Arab
strategy for peace negotiations with Israel.
   Hussein spoke to reporters at a briefing with President Hosni
Mubarak and PLO chief Yasser Arafat after they talked nearly five
hours about coordinating a Middle East peace strategy.
   The meeting was in preparation for Mubarak's talks in April and
Hussein's in May with President Bush in Washington.
   Mubarak said a major aim of his Washington talks is to seek
agreement on an international Middle East peace conference.
   Hussein told reporters the four countries decided on the boycott
threat recently when they formed a common market called the Arab
Cooperation Council.
   ``There have been calls for an ordinary or extraordinary Arab
summit,'' Hussein said. ``We are always for a summit and the
members of the Arab Cooperation Council will attend any summit
together. This is a decision we have taken: to attend together.''
   Asked if the opposite was true, Hussein nodded and said: ``Yes.''
   The Arab League froze Egypt's membership in 1979 after it signed
a peace treaty with Israel. Of its 21 member states, only Syria and
Libya oppose Egypt's readmission.
   The Ismailiya summit was held on the eve of the 10th anniversary
of the Camp David treaty, the first and only one between an Arab
country and the Jewish state, which is opposed to an international
conference.
   Egyptian officials said the three-way summit came amid
``encouraging developments,'' including Wednesday's meeting in
Tunisia between U.S. and Palestine Liberation Organization
representatives, which got down to substantive issues for the first
time since the dialogue began last December.
   The officials, who demanded anonymity, also cited Bush's praise
of the dialogue in a newspaper interview in which he said he would
try to convince Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir that
``something good might come'' from this.
   Bush is to meet Mubarak on April 3, Shamir on April 6 and
Hussein on May 2.
</TEXT>
