<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-89 1647EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FlagArtRevenge     03-25 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flag Art Revenge,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Artist Gets Revenge When Own Version Of Flag Exhibit Opens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An art teacher angered over an exhibit that
prompted viewers to trample a U.S. flag and sparked waves of
protest got revenge Saturday, offering observers a chance to walk
on a caricature of the display's artist.
   The teacher's exhibit, which opened Saturday at the small
Vietnam Museum, features a life-size sketch of artist ``Dread''
Scott Tyler, drawn on cloth in the manner of a police outline of a
homicide victim.
   The cloth is on the floor, and a U.S. flag hangs above it on a
museum wall.
   ``I was upset by seeing my flag on the floor,'' said Gary Mann,
33, a junior high school art teacher from suburban Deerfield, as
visitors walked over his artwork.
   Mann's display is a protest against Tyler's exhibit at the Art
Institute of Chicago's school, which led to daily protests by
hundreds of demonstrators outside the respected museum in early
March. Tyler is a student at the institute's school.
   His exhibit, which has since closed, featured a flag positioned
on the floor in front of a book asking viewers to write their
opinions on ``What is the Proper Way to Display a U.S. Flag?''
   Mann's exhibit is called, ``How to Display ``Dread'' Scott
Tyler,'' and also offers viewers a chance to record their reactions.
   One woman visitor to the cramped, storefront Vietnam Museum,
wrote, ``An artist he is not, this Dread Scott. He is an
unpatriotic snot. He knows not what this country is about.''
   ``I would do anything short of killing you to stop you,'' wrote
another visitor. ``Where you go, we will be. God Bless America.''
   Tyler, who calls himself a revolutionary, has an unlisted
telephone number and could not located for comment.
   Vietnam Museum owner Joe Hertel said he contacted Mann and asked
him to exhibit the display at his museum after hearing news reports
on it.
   ``It showed contempt for the artist who showed contempt for the
flag,'' said Hertel, a Vietnam veteran himself.
   Mann, who said he graduated from the School of the Art Institute
in 1976, plans to move the exhibit to various Veterans of Foreign
Wars halls around the state.
   Leonard and Ruth Bielski, both 65, said they came to see Mann's
exhibit because they could not be among the marchers at the Art
Institute during the controversy.
   ``The Art Institute was wrong in letting him do that in the
first place,'' said Bielski, a veteran of World War II.
   ``I'm ashamed because I went to the Art Institute myself,'' Mrs.
Bielski said. She said she graduated in 1938.
   Art Institute officials have defended the flag display and the
student's right to freedom of expression. But veterans and
protesters suceeded in temporarily shutting down the exhibit
several times. It closed March 16 after a month of controversy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890325-0100 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-89 1650EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Turkey     03-25 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turkey,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ozal Mixes Threats, Promises In the Face of Slipping Support</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EMEL ANIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Turgut Ozal struggled to improve
the chances of the Motherland Party in Sunday's local elections as
public opinion polls indicated it would draw only about 31 percent
of the vote.
   The center-right party attracted 36 percent in the last general
elections in 1987 and 41.6 percent in local polls five years ago.
   Surveys also predict Motherland will lose the races for mayor in
Ankara, the capital, and Izmir, the third-largest city. Mayor
Bedrettin Dalan was expected to carry Istanbul, the cultural and
financial center, for the party.
   The opposition has been portraying the elections as an
indication of national mood.
   Seven parties are competing to elect thousands of mayors, city
council members, provincial assembly members, village leaders and
neighborhood representatives.
   Motherland's major rival is the Social Democrat Populist Party,
led by Erdal Inonu and made up of many politicians who served in
the governments of former Premier Bulent Ecevit in 1970s.
   Surveys predicted that the True Path Party, headed by former
Premier Suleyman Demirel, would come in third.
   The 61-year-old Ozal has combined promises of expanded democracy
with threats to resign in his efforts to improve Motherland Party's
chances.
   The prime minister, who has been accused of nepotism by the
opposition, pledged to reshape his Cabinet the day after elections.
Party sources say Ozal's brother Yusuf and his cousin Husnu Dogan
may be left out of the Cabinet.
   Ozal, once lauded at home and abroad as Turkey's economic
miracle-maker, proposed working with the opposition to fashion a
new constitution for Turkey that would bolster democratic freedoms
and lift the ban on communist and religious parties.
   The constitution was enacted in 1982 by the then-ruling
military. It has come under fire as having too many restrictions on
freedom of expression, labor rights and academic autonomy.
   The Motherland Party also has promised voters to reduce income
tax withholding and to grant housing credits that were halted as a
measure against inflation, which hit 75 percent last year.
   Then, on Friday, Ozal told a news conference he would quit if
major opposition gains in the polls made it difficult for him to
govern. On Friday evening, in a TV campaign appearance, he asked
Turks to remember the turbulent 1970s, when terrorism and an
economic crisis paved the way for the 1980 military takeover.
   ``Anrchy will come back to haunt the country, the shortages and
lines for necessities will return,'' if the opposition gains, Ozal
said.
   Motherland Party mayors have completed huge water and sewage
projects and started low-cost housing projects to replace slums
surrounding their cities.
   But it is Ozal's overall record that has been the main campaign
issue.
   Accusations involving inflation, nepotism and corruption in high
places appear to have made an impression on voters, despite
economic advances marked by a $1.5 billion surplus last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
