<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0519 03-25 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0519,0606</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrian Army Gunners Clash With Christian Army</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with more killed, wounded in nighttime
bombardment. Pickup 8th graf pvs, ``Is this ...'' Note contents of 8th
graf, language may be offensive to some readers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Christian army commander accused
Syrian gunners of trying to assassinate him by shelling the
presidential palace Saturday. Police said 11 people were killed and
61 wounded in artillery duels.
   A communique from Gen. Michel Aoun's command said the palace in
suburban Baabda came under a sustained barrage of rockets ``in a
second attempt to assassinate the head of the legitimate
government.''
   Aoun, who heads the Christian cabinet in Lebanon's dual
government, charged Syrian gunners blasted his military
headquarters near Baabda March 14 in an attempt to kill him.
   At least one civilian was killed and another was wounded in the
Baabda attack Saturday, police said. The two-story hilltop palace
sustained extensive damage but Aoun and aides were uninjured, his
communique said.
   At least five people were killed and 30 wounded when artillery
barrages resumed in Beirut late Saturday, police reported.
   The new casualties raised the toll to 92 killed and 314 wounded
since March 8, when the latest round in Lebanon's 14-year-old civil
war broke out.
   Tens of thousands of panicky Beirut residents scurried back to
basements and bomb shelters for a third straight night as deafening
blasts resounded across the capital.
   ``Is this a way to celebrate Easter?'' cried Zeina Touk, a
Christian housewife reached by telephone at the shelter of her
apartment building in east Beirut. ``Damn them all.''
   Christian radio stations called the bombardment ``an Easter gift
from Syria.'' Moslem broadcasts blamed the escalation on Aoun's
forces.
   During the day, Aoun's 20,000 predominantly Christian troops and
an alliance of Syrian regulars and Druse militiamen fought sporadic
artillery duels around Beirut.
   Syrian troops joined Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt's militiamen
earlier this week in renewed sectarian fighting.
   Syria, the main powerbroker in this divided country, keeps
40,000 troops in Lebanon under a 1976 Arab League mandate to end
the civil war. It also supports a rival Moslem cabinet led by Salim
Hoss.
   A police spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
the new casualties were civilians. He said no Christian soldiers
were injured, and he knew nothing of any Syrian or Druse casualties.
   The barrage early Saturday against the Christian towns north of
Beirut reached as high as 80 rounds per minute before tapering off
into sporadic exchanges at daybreak, police said.
   About 1 million Christians, one quarter of Lebanon's population,
live in the crescent-shaped, 300-square mile enclave that comprises
around 10 percent of the country's territory.
   The Mediterranean runs along the western border of the Christian
enclave but Syrian troops and allied Moslem-leftist militiamen have
surrounded the enclave's eastern border.
   Christian radio and television stations interrupted their
programs late Friday to broadcast a statement by Aoun's command
warning residents of Moslem west Beirut to take ``maximum
precautions.''
   The statement said Aoun's command had monitored orders from the
Syrian command to shell Moslem areas ``to provoke the local
militias into responding against us.''
   The latest bout in fighting began 18 days ago when Aoun imposed
a blockade of illegal militia-run ports along Lebanon's coast. The
illegal ports have meant losses in Lebanese tax revenues of an
estimated $100 million a year.
   The Syrian-backed Moslem cabinet repudiated Aoun's action. In
retaliation, Moslem and Syrian forces imposed a blockade of the
Christian enclave.
</TEXT>
