<FIRST>r a AM-SpringBreak 1stLd-Writethru a0495 03-25 0779</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spring Break, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0495,0799</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party Till You Drop Is Name Of The Game</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 16th graf, `Once again...', to UPDATE
with fatal crash of plane towing advertising banner. Picks up 17th graf
pvs, `To the...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DBH1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Life in the fast lane moves at 10 mph
on the ``World's Most Famous Beach,'' where the unofficial mottos
during spring break are ``party till you drop'' and ``sun your
buns.''
   Some half-million college students have invaded the resort for
the 85-degree weather and the opportunity to watch scantily clad
members of the opposite sex burn lobster-pink in the bright
sunshine.
   ``This is the largest crowd to ever hit Daytona Beach. Traffic
is snarled. Every parking space on the beach is taken, plus all the
private and public parking near the beach,'' said Beach Department
Chief John Kirvin. ``At times, you can't even find any sand.''
   Sightseeing is one of the most popular activities.
   ``I came here to look at the boys ... I mean men ... to look at
tan chests,'' said Michelle Abbott, a junior at the University of
Kansas.
   And to remember their days on the beach when they return to
college, both men and women aren't the least bit shy about
photographing the opposite sex.
   ``I'm on my second roll (of film) today and and I've got four
more after that,'' said Larry Turner, a botany student at Southern
Illinois, as he focused on a young woman strolling down the sand.
   Some men carried signs urging young women to take off their
bikini tops. One group of women carried a sign urging men to drop
their trunks.
   ``If their parents only knew what their daughters were doing,''
said a beach police officer who asked not to be identified.
   The ``party till you drop'' action moves from hotel pool decks
onto the beach in early afternoon, Kirvin said.
   He estimated that some 200 people have been arrested on the
beach, most for disorderly conduct and alcohol-related offenses.
   Alcohol is not allowed on the beach, but if students follow an
officer's warning to get rid of it they are not charged.
   There is no way, he said, that his 36 full-time officers and 15
part-timers can stop everyone drinking on 40 miles of beach.
   ``We try to curb it with selective enforcement,'' he said.
``Most of the kids are super and very cooperative.''
   Conditions were quite different out West, where spring break at
the desert resort of Palm Springs, Calif., was marred by hundreds
of arrests this year. Police in riot gear were called to one hotel
late Friday after young people began fighting, breaking windows and
throwing trash, authorities said.
   Once again in Daytona Beach, hotel balcony accidents take their
toll. So far this year, four people have fallen, including a
22-year-old Illinois man who died Thursday after lunging from a
balcony to catch a Frisbee. Last year, one person was killed and
seven were injured in balcony falls.
   On Saturday, a single-engine airplane towing an advertising
banner crashed into the ocean just off neighboring Daytona Beach
Shores, killing the pilot, authorities said.
   The aircraft, owned by Aerial Messenger of New Smyrna Beach,
went down in clear weather about a half-mile offshore, said Arthur
Sterritt, a Volusia County sheriff's deputy. The name of the pilot,
who was the only person on board, was not immediately released.
   To the south, former spring break capital Fort Lauderdale
expected fewer than 20,000 students this year, as a result of
strict city rules on drinking and cruising. As many as 350,000
students descended on Fort Lauderdale for spring break in 1985.
   Daytona officials say Fort Lauderdale's loss of college students
is their gain.
   ``They've always been welcome here,'' said Georgia Carter,
publicity manager for Destination Daytona, a branch of the Visitors
and Convention Bureau. ``We've had spring break since the '50s, but
it's just gotten bigger and bigger since Fort Lauderdale decided
they didn't want them there anymore.''
   But why did students endure long hours of travel to reach
Daytona's beach?
   ``I'm a senior and it's mandatory,'' said Joe Marcus, of
Blacksburg, Va., a Virginia Tech student. ``Last year I went to Key
West. This is better.''
   Kevin Lockwood and some friends drove 14 hours from Southern
Illinois University.
   ``I'm here for the sun and the girls and the beer,'' said
Lockwood, a junior conservation enforcement major at SIU.
   ``We read about Daytona in Playboy. We saw the pictures,'' said
Kurt Brewer, a senior chemical engineering major at the University
of Kansas. ``But we're actually here to get away from Dorothy and
Toto.''
</TEXT>
