<HEAD>Police Arrest Man Identified As Supplier Of Killer Brew</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested a man identified as a
supplier for the illegally brewed liquor that killed more than 130
people in the western Indian city of Baroda, news reports said
Saturday.
   The man was arrested late Friday, Press Trust of India said. The
dispatch did not say if charges were filed.
   Three people were arrested earlier for allegedly manufacturing
and selling the poisonous liquor, PTI said. One of those people
identified the man arrested Friday as the supplier of the methyl
alcohol that made the liquor deadly, the news agency said.
   The illegal brew was made from methyl alcohol instead of its
normal ethyl alcohol base. Methyl alcohol paralyses the central
nervous system, causing death.
   The mass poisoning was the worst ever in Gujarat state, where
more than 300 people have died in similar tragedies since 1981.
Gujarat is the only Indian state that has banned the sale of
alcohol.
</TEXT>
