<SECOND>AM-BRF--Belgium-Airport,0146</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air controllers end strike that stranded thousands of travelers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air traffic controllers returned to
their jobs late Saturday, ending a strike that caused delays for
thousands of Easter holiday travelers at Brussels International
Airport.
   The controllers began their strike Friday. They agreed to go
back to work after reaching an interim agreement with the
government on terms for new negotiations. Controllers are seeking
salary increases and improved working conditions.
   More than 100 planes had been grounded since late Friday, and
about as many incoming flights were diverted to other airports.
   Officials said airport operations would not return to normal
until Monday.
   At about noon Saturday some 5,000 travelers were stranded at the
Brussels airport, located in Zaventem. Some were taken to airports
in Luxembourg, France and Germany, but those facilities also were
crowded with weekend traffic.
