<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Bishop     03-25 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Bishop,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anglican Bishop Does Not Believe in Jesus' Physical Resurrection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bishop of Durham, a familiar voice of
controversy in the Church of England, has reiterated his belief
that the resurrection of Jesus Christ was spiritual rather than
physical.
   The remarks of the Rt. Rev. David Jenkins, recorded for
broadcast Sunday by Tyne Tees Television, immediately drew
suggestions he be replaced.
   Jenkins has frequently fueled controversy in the state church by
publicly questioning the literal truth of several basic Christian
beliefs, including the virgin birth and Jesus' rising from the dead.
   Some church members said it was an ``act of God'' when the great
York Minster cathedral was struck by lightning and badly burned
three days after Jenkins' consecration there as bishop in 1984.
   In remarks for broadcast Easter Sunday, Jenkins said knowing
Christ was alive was an inner feeling that did not need the
physical proof of a corpse returning to life.
   ``I don't think it means a physical resurrection. It means a
spiritual resurrection, a transforming resurrection, a real
resurrection.
   ``Because the experiencing, which enabled people to know that
Jesus was alive beyond death, must be more than the revival of a
corpse,'' Jenkins said.
   Geoffrey Dickens, a Conservative member of Parliament, accused
Jenkins of ``seeking to undermine the whole doctrine of the
church.''
   ``It would certainly be beneficial if ways could be found to
remove him from office,'' he said.
   Neil Hamilton, another Tory legislator, added: ``When will the
archbishop of Canterbury give a lead and speak out against this
man?''
   Jenkins said he was sure the disciples did not think of the
Resurrection as a physical phenomenon.
   ``If you read the echoes of the narratives, let alone what St.
Paul says, I don't think it means a physical resurrection at all.
It's a real presence, a real renewal of personality which is now
transformed, to be alive forever,'' he said.
   Sir Nicholas Fairbairn, also a Conservative legislator, said of
the bishop: ``Does he not know that Christ appeared before his
disciples and when they doubted he actually showed them the wounds
of the nails on the cross?''
   Another Tory, Irvine Patnick, commented: ``I am sure
Christianity, which has been going on for 1,989 years, will
continue despite his sudden statement which demolishes the church
and its teaching.''
   Controversy over Jenkins' beliefs prompted a church doctrine
study in 1987. A commission of 14 theologians decided such
controversies are ``a sign of vitality in the church.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
