<SECOND>AM-Iraq-Saudi,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Saudi King Opens Talks in Iraq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Fahd of Saudi Arabia received a
red-carpet welcome at the Baghdad airport Saturday as he began the
first visit to Iraq by a Saudi monarch in 30 years.
   He was greeted at Saddam International Airport by President
Saddam Hussein, and the two rode in an open limousine through
streets lined with thousands of flag-waving people to the Dijlah
government guest house.
   Before opening talks with Saddam, Fahd issued a statment saying,
``We have stood and will continue standing with Iraq in its
attempts to achieve lasting and comprehensive peace and until it
will be capable of continuing its development and construction
plans.''
   The official Iraqi News Agency quoted Fahd as saying he would
discuss with Saddam the Palestinian issue, Afghanistan, Lebanon and
Iraq's reconstruction following its eight-year war with Iran.
   Saudi Arabia and most Arab nations backed Arab Iraq in its war
against Persian Iran that began in September 1980. Hostilities
ended with a cease-fire in August.
   Reports in Iraq's government-run news media praised Saudi Arabia
for its support during the war. It is believed the Saudis provided
Iraq with billions of dollars in financial aid and logistical
support.
   Earlier this month, Saudi Arabia ordered that construction
materials be shipped to Iraq's war-battered southern port of Basra.
   Fahd is to travel to Cairo Monday for a four-day visit.
   He last visited Baghdad in 1978, four years before becoming king.
</TEXT>
