<FIRST>r a AM-KimballSettlement     03-25 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kimball Settlement,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Olympic Diver's Insurance Company Settles With Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Clif in 7th graf is cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Olympic diver Bruce Kimball's
insurance companies will pay a total of $1.3 million to five
victims of a car wreck that killed two teen-agers and injured six
others last August, the athlete's attorney has announced.
   Attorney James A. Murman said Friday there is ``an agreement in
principle'' to resolve four lawsuits filed against the former U.S.
team diver, who won a silver medal in the 1984 Olympics.
   Kimball's insurers also will give money to an injured youth who
sought compensation but did not file a lawsuit, Murman said.
   Kimball was driving his sports car last Aug. 1 when it sped into
a crowd of youths gathered outside a popular hangout on a rural
road near Brandon, just east of Tampa. He was convicted of
drunken-driving manslaughter and sentenced to 17 years in prison.
   He plans to ask a judge next week to reduce his sentence to a
term of less than 10 years and allow him to be transferred from the
maximum security Tomoka Correctional Institution to a facility
where he can be treated for a ``chemical dependency,'' according to
his criminal defense lawyer, Frank Quesada.
   Meanwhile, attorneys involved in the lawsuits against Kimball
hope to sign the settlement within two weeks, Murman said. They
would not discuss how the money will be divided among the victims
and their families.
   ``It's a fair settlement based on the amount of money and assets
that were available from Mr. Kimball,'' said Clif Curry, a Brandon
attorney who represents two of the victims.
   Murman said he spoke recently with Kimball at the Daytona Beach
prison. The Michigan native wants to put the lawsuits behind him,
his civil lawyer said.
   ``He wanted to be sure the victims were compensated, and it
appears they will be,'' Murman said.
   Those killed in the crash were Robbie Bedell, 19, and Kevin
Gossic, 16. Their families filed wrongful death claims against
Kimball last fall, contending his driving was grossly negligent.
   The parents of April Bruffy, 19, and R.J. Kerker, 17, also sued,
holding Kimball accountable for their children's serious leg
injuries. James Cable, 19, injured an ankle in the crash. He did
not file a lawsuit, but will receive compensation anyway, Murman
said.
   The money will come from Kimball's two insurers, Cincinnati
Insurance Co. and AAA Automobile Club of Michigan Group. Cincinnati
will provide about $1 million and AAA will offer about $300,000,
sources said.
</TEXT>
