<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-25 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wet Weather West Of Rockies, Snow In Maine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A moist Pacific weather system spread showers across most of the
western third of the nation Saturday, and locally heavy snow fell
overnight in Maine.
   Most of California had rain Saturday and rain also fell over
much of the Pacific Northwest and sections of the Intermountain
region between the Sierra Nevada and the Rockies.
   The heaviest rain fell in northern California, but southern
California also was hit and most of the Los Angeles area received a
steady light rain during the morning, with amounts generally around
a quarter of an inch.
   In California's Sierra Nevada range, over 3 inches of rain fell
during the 24 hours ending at 7 a.m. EST at Blue Canyon and at La
Porte, which got 3.56 inches.
   Precipitation at Blue Canyon changed to snow late in the
morning. Some higher elevations in the northern Sierra Nevada got
around 1 to 2 feet of snow.
   Gusty wind developed over parts of the Southwest during the day
with a gust to 49 mph reported at Cedar City, Calif.
   In the Northeast, much of Maine had heavy snow overnight,
including 11 inches at Lewiston, 8 inches at Augusta, 6 inches at
Rumford, and 4 inches at Portland.
   That snow changed to rain during the morning and most of it
ended by midday. Afternoon temperatures in the upper 30s and 40s
throughout the state melted much of the snow.
   Elsewhere, showers were scattered over eastern sections of the
Dakotas and western Minnesota. In eastern North Dakota, most of the
precipitation was in the form of snow or sleet.
   Showers spread over northern Michigan, with almost a half-inch
of precipitation at Pellston.
   A flow of air off the Gulf of Mexico brought ashore enough
moisture to produce widely scattered showers over southern Texas.
   Much of the nation had sunshine and mild temperatures and warm
air pushed northward across the Plains, producing noon readings of
68 at Rapid City, S.D.; 69 at Denver, and 71 at Chadron, Neb.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 29
degrees at South Lake Tahoe, Calif., to 88 at Altus Air Force Base,
Okla. Saturday's low in the Lower 48 states was 21 degrees at
Devils Lake, N.D.
   For Sunday, showers were forecast across the West from the
Rockies to the Pacific Coast. Snow showers were forecast in much of
Nevada and the mountains of Arizona. Scattered showers and
thunderstorms were forecast from southern and eastern Texas into
western Louisiana and Arkansas.
   Highs in the 40s and 50s were predicted from the Pacific
Northwest to the northern Rockies, along the Canadian border from
Montana to Michigan, and over most of New York state and New
England; in the 80s from Texas across the central Gulf Coast states
to South Carolina, Georgia and Florida; and in the 60s and 70s
across much of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
