<SECOND>AM-South Korea-Japan,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Freed Japanese Businessman Given Embassy Protection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Japanese businessmen held captive
for 33 days by officials of a Korean firm in a business dispute is
now under the protection of the Japanese Embassy, police said
Saturday.
   They said Tokuo Osawa, president of the Tokyo-based Osawa Press
Seisakusho machinery company, was released in Seoul Friday and
turned over to the Japanese Embassy.
   Officials at the embassy were not available for comment.
   Osawa, 54, was taken to a hospital for a medical examination and
then tranferred to a Seoul hotel under embassy protection,
according to police.
   ``He is in good health and will be allowed to leave Korea after
an investigation,'' said one Korean official who spoke on condition
of anonymity.
   He reported Japanese Embassy personnel said Osawa was seized by
officials of the Namil Machine Co. at a Seoul restaurant on Feb. 20
and taken to the Namil plant in Chinchun, 80 miles south of Seoul,
where he was held until Friday.
   Local newspapers said Osawa was released after agreeing to pay
about $385,000 in compensation for allegedly defective machines his
firm sold to Namil last year. They said Osawa's company sold six
machines to Namil for $1.07 million, and that Osawa came to South
Korea after the Korean firm complained that the machines did not
operate correctly.
   A spokesman at Osawa's company in Tokyo said Osawa had been held
by Namil officials for several days in December but was freed
because of actions by the Japanese Embassy and Korean police.
   He said that after Osawa was released in December, he was not
allowed to leave South Korea because of a lawsuit filed by Namil.
</TEXT>
