<FIRST>r a AM-Gotti-BombSuspect     03-25 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gotti-Bomb Suspect,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Looking For Hospital Employee In Gotti Bomb Scare</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERENA DOBNIK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police are searching for a hospital employee who
claims he planted the fake bomb intended for reputed organized
crime boss John Gotti, officers said Saturday.
   The employee, Michael McCray, called WCBS-TV in New York to say
he is waging a war against drugs and to claim responsibility for
leaving the device outside a Little Italy social club, said Barbara
Nevins, a correspondent at the station.
   She said she met the 37-year-old New York man Wednesday in
Pittsburgh, where he stopped while driving west, a day after he
called the TV station. WCBS reported the story Friday.
   Police consider McCray a suspect and are trying to locate him
for questioning, police Sgt. Maurice Howard said Saturday.
   Nevins said police believe that only the person who built the
fake bomb could describe in as much detail as McCray did.
   However, Howard would not confirm whether McCray is the chief
suspect in the case or if he had provided convincing detail about
the device.
   The fake bomb, a plastic box containing salt and gunpowder, was
found Monday after an anonymous caller told police a ``gift'' for
Gotti had been left at the Ravenite Social Club, where police
suspect Gotti conducts mob business.
   Nevins said McCray told her he was ``fed up with drugs and drug
dealers'' and that he ``wanted to send a message to John Gotti.''
He said he had written several letters to Gotti warning him to get
out of the drug trade.
   McCray told Nevins he is aware Gotti had never been charged with
drug-related crimes.
   McCray is a medical photographer at North Shore University
Hospital in Manhasset, according to Dan Rosett, a spokesman for the
hospital. He said he did not know when McCray would return to work,
but that he was ``an employee of the hospital as of Friday.''
   A friend of McCray described him as ``a sincere and concerned
person who gets very involved in causes,'' according to Nevins. He
said he feels he's on a crusade against drugs and thought he would
get attention for his cause with the incident, according to Nevins.
</TEXT>
