<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-89 1817EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Sudan 1stLd-Writethru   03-25 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0524,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mahdi's New Sudanese `Peace' Cabinet Sworn In</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with all new Cabinet ministers sworn
in. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The broad-based ``peace'' Cabinet of
Prime Minister Sadek el-Mahdi was sworn in Saturday shortly after
the State Council, Sudan's collective presidency, endorsed all 23
candidates.
   The Cabinet included almost all the nation's political groups as
well as the powerful trade unions.
   The fundamentalist National Islamic Front, however, boycotted
the new government for adopting a program calling for suspending
Islamic law as a prelude for making peace with the rebel Sudan
People's Liberation Army.
   The rebel army now seems to have the upper hand in the south.
Its forces have captured major garrison towns in the last few
months.
   Relief agencies blame Sudan's six-year civil war for
contributing to famine in the south that U.N. officials say killed
500,000 people last year.
   Saturday's swearing-in ended a political crisis that had
confronted Mahdi since January. The Democratic Unionist Party, a
partner in his Cabinet, resigned then to protest Mahdi's refusal to
endorse a peace agreement the party signed Nov. 16 with the
Liberation Army.
   Under a program signed by Mahdi and 65 heads of political
parties and unions, the new government will immediately endorse the
Nov. 16 accord. It will eventually hold a national constitutional
conference with all powers in Sudan participating, including the
rebels, to end the war.
   Mahdi offered his Cabinet's resignation two weeks ago, bowing to
pressure from the military, political parties and trade and
professional unions for a widely representative government that
would begin peace talks with the rebels.
   Many of the new ministers served in previous governments.
   The defense post went to an independent, retired Gen. Mubarak
Osaman Rahma, who has served as a diplomat in Moscow and Eastern
Europe.
   Eight ministries went to Mahdi's centrist Umma party; six to the
centrist Democratic Unionists; four to the southern parties; two to
the unions; one to leftists; one to the western Sudan National
Party and one to an independent.
   Mahdi became prime minister in 1986, a year after the military
overthrew President Gaafar Nimeiri and then handed power to the
civilians after general elections.
   Rebels in the mainly Christian and animist south took up arms
against the Arab Moslem majority government in the north in 1983.
They demand more autonomy as well as economic and administrative
reforms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
