<DOCNO> AP890325-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-89 1831EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Gramm-CampaignFine     03-25 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gramm-Campaign Fine,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senator Agrees To Settle Election Dispute, Pay $30,000</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, announced Saturday
his 1984 campaign committee has agreed to pay a $30,000 penalty to
settle a 5-year dispute with the Federal Election Commission.
   Although errors made by his first Senate campaign committee were
``unintended and in no way benefitted the campaign ... they were
errors,'' Gramm said.
   ``The FEC does not contend that anyone in the campaign committee
consciously sought to violate any FEC reporting requirement and the
committee is now in total compliance. They were technical reporting
errors and they in no way benefitted my campaign,'' said Gramm, who
intends to seek re-election in 1990.
   In a statement, Gramm said he rejected suggestions that he take
the FEC to court to fight the penalty as ``unfair and unjustified''
because a lawsuit would cost many times the $30,000 penalty.
   Donald R. White, treasurer of the ``Friends of Phil Gramm'' 1984
Senate campaign committee, said the FEC accused the group of
failure to make timely reports and failure to supply adequate
documentation of campaign contributions.
   According to White, the FEC questioned the campaign's handling
of contributions from husbands and wives on joint checking
accounts. The FEC has found that $15,000 of $690,000 in potentially
excess contributions was outside the limit of $1,000 per person,
per election.
   After the committee provided documentation on the questionable
contributions, the FEC decided $675,000 was within the limits. The
remaining $15,000 will be donated to charity, White said.
   Also, the FEC questioned whether the campaign fully reported
primary debts, which White said were accurate, although most of the
debt had not been billed to the campaign by the time original
reports were to have been filed. The FEC also determined that
$9,708 in corporate funds were erroneously accepted. The money has
been refunded, White said.
   The FEC complained that contributor identification data such as
addresses and job title were not always available in a timely
manner and not all funds were deposited within 10 days of receipt.
White said both assertions were correct in ``scattered'' instances,
and that complete information on each contributor was provided to
the FEC.
   Finally, the FEC complained that the campaign overpaid its share
of a joint fund-raiser at the 1984 Republican National Convention
in Dallas. White said a campaign audit found the complaint to be
accurate and has agreed to seek a $506 reimbursement from the only
remaining co-host, the National Republican Senatorial Committee.
   Two other co-hosts, the Texas Victory '84 Fund and the
Republican Host Committee, have been disbanded.
   ``In no way did the failure to obtain written allocation of
funds on joint checking accounts, the failure to report debt in the
primary, the overpayment of the committee's share of fund-raising
costs or any other reporting error in any way benefit the Gramm
campaign,'' White said.
   ``The plain truth is that a flood of 70,000 individual
contributions defeated the efforts of our volunteer campaign
workers to adequately screen and process the incoming mail,'' he
said.
   Gramm said his 1990 re-election committee will be staffed by a
professional team of certified public accountants, attorneys and
managers ``to assure that the problems of the 1984 campaign reports
never occur again.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890325-0115 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-89 1844EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Obit-Mufti     03-25 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Mufti,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Jordanian Prime Minister Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Al-Mufti, a former Jordanian prime minister
who helped lead his country to become an independent kingdom, died
on Saturday, state-run Jordan Television reported.
   The report gave no details, including where Mufti died, the
cause of death or his age.
   Mufti was one of Jordan's most prominent citizens throughout the
country's 68-year history as an emirate under British protection
and later as an independent monarchy.
   A strong nationalist, he balked at the 1928 constitutional
agreement with Britain, claiming it gave Britain too much say in
Jordan's affairs. Britain was responsible for Jordan under a League
of Nations mandate. Jordan became an independent monarchy in 1946.
   As prime minister from April to December 1950, Mufti opposed
King Abdullah's negotiations with Israel.
   During his second term as prime minister in 1956, Mufti
expressed reservations about the Baghdad Pact, a U.S.-backed plan
to create a belt of anti-communist nations from Turkey to Iran.
   He was a major figure in the regency council that governed
Jordan between the abdication of King Talal in 1952 and the 1953
accession of King Hussein, then a teen-ager.
   Mufti was leader of Jordan's small community of Circassians, who
had emigrated to Jordan from the Russian empire in the 19th century
and who became a bedrock of support for the current Hashemite
monarchy.
   He served repeatedly in Jordanian cabinets from 1929 until the
early 1960s, often as deputy prime minister and as interior
minister.
   One of Mufti's sons, Azmi Al-Mufti, was assassinated in 1985
while serving as ambassador to Greece. Jordanian diplomats at the
time were targets of a wave of terrorist attacks by Syrian-backed
Palestinian factions opposed to Hussein's efforts to reach peace
with Israel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890325-0116 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-89 1847EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-TreatyRetrospective 2ndLd-Writehthru a05neia</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Treaty Retrospective, 2nd Ld-Writehthru, a0538,1180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Experts Agree 1979 Accord Has Worked But Find Mideast Momentum Lost</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 10th graf to give exact date of accord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Middle East landscape is vastly and
dramatically changed since Israel and Egypt signed their historic
peace treaty a decade ago. Palestinian Arabs are in revolt and
their cause is being promoted with the Bush administration by
nations around the world.
   Four key American players at the time and a former special U.S.
mediator all agree that the treaty has served the cause of peace in
the troubled Middle East.
   ``It changed the map of the Middle East and, to a degree, its
political climate,'' says Cyrus R. Vance, who was secretary of
state when Egypt and Israel decided to turn from war to peace.
   ``It established a precedent and provided a foundation on which
one can still build,'' says Zbigniew Brzezinski, who was former
President Jimmy Carter's national security adviser in those parlous
days.
   ``The good news is the treaty has lasted,'' says William Quandt,
who was the National Security Council's Mideast specialist.
   ``It's a framework that has really held up,'' says Harold
Saunders, who headed the Near East bureau at the State Department.
   ``The dramatic fact is not a single Israeli or Egyptian soldier
has been killed on that border since the treaty went into effect,''
says Sol Linowitz, who subsequently served as Carter's special
emissary to the Middle East.
   But all five, interviewed separately for the 10th anniversary of
the treaty, registered impatience and disappointment with what the
consider to be a lack of accomplishment in the years since.
   They hope President Bush and Secretary of State James A. Baker
III will recapture the spirit and drive of Camp David and apply it
to Israel and the Palestinian Arabs, thousands of whom are in
rebellion on the West Bank and in Gaza.
   For 11 exhausting days to September 17, 1978 Carter shuttled
between the cabins of the late Egyptian President Anwar Sadat and
then-Israeli Prime Minister Menachem Begin in the presidential
retreat in Maryland's Catoctin mountains and cajoled them into a
peace accord that took the largest and most powerful Arab country
out of the conflict with Israel.
   The treaty, which also required Israel, the victor in the 1967
Six-Day War, to return all captured territory to Egypt, the
vanquished, needed more than Carter's heavy lifting at Camp David
to be nailed down. He had to go to the Middle East and keep Sadat
and Begin from flying apart again.
   It was a high-wire act, but it worked.
   Israel would like a warmer relationship from Egypt _ more trade,
tourism and the other trappings of friendship. Egypt would like
Israel to give up the rest of the land the Arabs lost in 1967. But
they are at peace.
   Vance, who negotiated several of the key provisions of the
treaty with the late Israeli Foreign Minister Moshe Dayan, said
from his New York law office: ``It has prevented another war
between Israel and its neighbors, and it has laid the first stones
for a just and enduring peace.''
   But Vance quickly added: ``I think the question we have to ask
ourselves now is how can we breath new life into the peace
process.''
   He suggested three ways:
   __ By demonstrating a willingness to try again, starting with
confidence-building measures.
   __ By being willing to engage in creative, fresh thinking __
``and a willingness to think the unthinkable.''
   __ By the parties to the Arab-Israeli conflict ``putting
themselves in the shoes of the person across the table.''
   Specifically, Vance said the time has come for direct talks
between Israel and the Palestinians _ including the Palestine
Liberation Organization.
   ``I still believe peace is possible,'' he said. ``But it's going
to take courage and great political will on the part of all
involved.''
   Vance doesn't mean only Arabs and Israelis. He also means the
United States.
   ``I think the United States has a clear and important role to
play, and I hope that the United States will put the Middle East
question on its agenda,'' he said. ``I have seen some recent signs
of this.''
   Brzezinski, who sometimes disagreed with Vance on other policy
issues when they served under Carter, voiced similar views in in a
separate interview from his Washington office.
   He called the treaty ``a partial success,'' but also ``a partial
failure'' and said ``the failure is obviously the absence of
progress on the West Bank issue.''
   The Camp David agreement, which established the outline for the
peace treaty, called for five years of autonomy for the
Palestinians on the Israeli-held West Bank and in Gaza. Afterward,
all options including statehood were to be open for negotiations.
   Brzezinski said the Palestinians have grown stronger since 1979.
He said the transitional period should be shortened and it should
lead to ``some form of statehood.''
   And that, he said, means Israel negotiating directly with the
PLO.
   Baker seems to be taking the first few steps in that direction.
He has not broken off U.S. talks with the PLO despite several
guerrilla attempts at infiltrating Israel. He has stressed his aim
is to bring Israelis and Palestinians together. And he has said
that might require Israel talking to the PLO.
   Quandt, a scholar who met recently with Chairman Yasser Arafat
and other PLO officials, said he had ``nothing against the notion
that incremental steps are valuable.''
   But, he said, events in the Middle East are accelerating.
``Israelis understand they are going to have to make a deal with
the Palestinians.'' Quandt said. ``And I think the Palestinians are
willing to talk to Israel, as it is.''
   Quandt summed up: ``I think we are in sight of Israeli-PLO
negotiations.''
   Saunders, like Quandt a Mideast scholar at the Brookings
Institution, offered this curbstone advice: ``A strong involvement
by the president and secretary of state is going to be necessary.
It's taken a lot of time for Egyptians and Israelis to learn to
talk to each other.
   ``The Israeli-Palestinian relationship today is a lot more fully
developed. Once they get together they are going to be able to do
more on their own than was in the case of Egypt and Israel.''
   Linowitz, who tried to build on the peace treaty as Carter's
Mideast envoy from late 1979 until the onset of the Reagan
administration in 1981, puts a lot of the blame for a lack of
progress on the West Bank and Gaza since the treaty on ``the
unwillingness of the United States to take real leadership.''
   He said he had urged Alexander M. Haig Jr., who had taken over
as secretary of state, to appoint a special emissary ``to pick up
the negotiations where they then were'' on the Palestinian issue.
   Linowitz said he thought at the time ``if that were done it
would be possible to have a treaty by May of 1981.``
   But, he said, ``the administration wanted to take its time, and
valuable time was lost.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Barry Schweid has covered U.S. diplomacy in the
Middle East for The Associated Press since 1973.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890325-0117 </DOCNO>
