<HEAD>Sikh Killed In Front Of Court In Kashmir</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JAMMU, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gunman on Saturday killed a Sikh who was
among scores of other people outside the Jammu-Kashmir state High
Court, police reported.
   Police Superintendent Jaswant Singh said 55-year-old Kalyan
Singh was shot by a man in his early 20s who escaped in the crowded
street in front of the court building.
   Police said they had not determined the motive for the killing
but that there might be a connection between the killer and Sikh
extremists in Punjab state, just south of Jammu-Kashmir.
   The courts were in session when the shooting occurred and some
were hearing cases involving Sikh militants from Punjab.
   Sikh extremists have been waging a bloody campaign since 1982
for the creation of an independent Sikh state in Punjab.
   The Sikh separatists claim Hindus discriminate against Sikhs.
   Sikhs slightly outnumber Hindus in Punjab, but they make up only
2 percent of India's overall population; Hindus comprise 82 percent.
