<HEAD>Avalanche Kills Woman, Buries Child in Norwegian Ski Cabin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIRDAL, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An avalanche crushed a family's mountain
ski cabin in southwestern Norway Saturday, killing a woman and
burying six others, police said.
   A 4-year-old girl, buried under the snow for more than two
hours, was hospitalized in critical condition, officials said. The
other survivors, including an infant, were located quickly and were
not seriously hurt, said Rogaland police Officer Leif Helge
Eskeland.
   ``It appears the entire family was in the cabin when the
avalanche hit,'' Eskeland said. Police would not identify the
seven, who were on an Easter skiing vacation.
   The avalanche swept through a popular winter cabin complex about
30 miles east of the city of Stavanger. It destroyed one cottage
and damaged another, said Red Cross spokesman Morten Halgunset.
   The Red Cross also reported that a 25-year-old Danish mountain
climber was killed Friday when he fell from one of Norway's
steepest mountain faces at Mount Kapelltind near Tromsoe in
northern Norway.
   His climbing partners reached help Saturday afternoon and a
rescue helicopter recovered the body, said the Norwegian news
agency NTB. Police would not identify the victim until his
relatives had been notified.
