<UNK>Newspaper Says Greens Party Member Linked to Libyan Lobby Group</UNK>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper reported Saturday that a
member of Parliament from the ecological Greens party has links to
a Libyan-financed foundation. Party leaders said they would
investiate the allegations.
   The Munich-based Sueddeutsche Zeitung said Alfred Mechtersheimer
was involved with the M.A.G. Foundation for Peace and Solidarity
based in Vaduz, Liechstenstein. It said the foundation was financed
by a $10 million account set up in Switzerland by Libyan leader
Col. Moammar Gadhafi.
   Mechtersheimer was quoted by the newspaper as saying he did not
have a special role with the foundation but acted ``as a kind of
adviser.''
   Antje Vollmer, a Greens spokeswoman, said a party meeting might
be convened to discuss the allegation.
   She said Greens leaders want to know more about the extent of
Mechtersheimer's connections to the foundation, who heads the
foundation and its purpose.
   Mechtersheimer could not be reached for comment Saturday.
   The newspaper quoted Mechtersheimer as saying the foundation was
set up to promote the ``new thinking'' in Libya.
   He said it was important that Libya not be isolated ``like the
Americans would have it'' and that efforts should be made to
``bring Libya closer to the world community,'' according to the
newspaper.
   It said he acknowledged that the M.A.G. in the title represents
Gadhafi's initials.
   The United States has accused the Gadhafi regime of supporting
international terrorism.
