<FIRST>r a AM-ThinBlueLine-Restitution     03-25 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thin Blue Line-Restitution,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Restitution To Adams Doubtful</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a0579 to change slug; a previous story, a0532,
has already moved as AM-Thin Blue Line.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Randall Dale Adams has little chance of getting
compensated for his 12{-year imprisonment and near-execution for a
police murder he didn't commit because Texas law protects his
prosecutors, experts say.
   ``Even if there's out and out misconduct ... even if he (the
prosecutor) lied ... you can't sue the prosecutor,'' Dallas civil
rights attorney Doug Larson said.
   Adams was freed last week after his conviction was overturned.
New evidence brought out in the film ``The Thin Blue Line'' had
strongly suggested that another man committed the killing.
   Adams' attorney, Randy Schaffer, said he hasn't discussed the
possibility of a lawsuit with his client, who has returned home to
Columbus, Ohio. But if Adams agrees, Schaffer said he has some
ideas.
   ``What I might do is sue (former Assistant District Attorney
Doug) Mulder and challenge him to waive any claim of prosecutorial
immunity,'' Schaffer said. ``If Doug Mulder feels that his conduct
was defensible, I challenge him to waive immunity and try this
matter on the merits.''
   ``On the other hand, if he concedes his conduct was illegal,
unethical and dishonest, then I invite him to invoke prosecutorial
immunity as a defense.''
   Schaffer said he also intends to ask the Texas Legislature to
authorize good-will compensation for Adams, who spent 12{ years in
prison and at one point was only three days away from being
executed for the slaying. His sentence was later commuted to life
imprisonment.
   Adams would not be the only Texas victim of wrongful conviction
unable to receive redress.
   Lenell Geter, who served 16 months of a life sentence after he
was wrongfully convicted of a 1982 robbery, saw his $8.2 million
federal lawsuit claiming civil rights violations dismantled last
year. Marvin Maurice Wells, whose 1986 capital murder trial was
halted when prosecutors found the right man, last year lost his
$6.5 million federal suit against the police.
   Randy Ty Senegar, who was imprisoned for 14 months after a 1986
rape victim mistakenly identified him as her masked attacker,
didn't even try to win compensation. His attorney, Roger Joyner,
told him Texas law made no provision for it.
   In fact, Joyner suggested that Senegar's case would be ruled
``frivolous,'' clearing the way for the state to sue him.
   Witnesses also are immune from lawsuits because the U.S. Supreme
Court has ruled that the threat of a lawsuit could prevent people
from testifying. The judge and jury are protected too.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
