<FIRST>r a AM-Escapee-Shooting     03-25 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Escapee-Shooting,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prison Escapee Arrested After Allegedly Shooting Officer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAK CREEK, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Indiana prison escapee and his female
accomplice, both suspected in an interstate crime spree, were
arrested and hospitalized Saturday after being chased by a wounded
police officer, authorities said.
   Both suspects were listed in critical condition at St. Luke's
Hospital in Racine from complications due to apparent drug
overdoses, officials said.
   Officers found Ronald R. Plummer, 39, and Elizabeth C.
Bonvillian, 31, hiding in a barn about 7 a.m., said Racine County
Sheriff's Deputy Kenneth Sowinski.
   ``They were found buried between straw in a box stall in the
barn,'' Sowinski said. ``Both appeared to be under the influence of
drugs so they were transported to a hospital for treatment.''
   A hospital spokesman said their condition worsened after their
arrival at the hospital. In addition, a police dog bit Plummer when
he refused to come out of hiding, authorities said.
   Sowinski said authorities suspect the two were involved in a
series of crimes that began Friday with Plummer's escape and a
hostage incident in Indianapolis and included an armed robbery in
Illinois and the shooting of the Oak Creek officer.
   Plummer, serving a federal prison term for bank robberies in
Ohio, had been in Indianapolis for a trial and awaiting sentencing
in another case. He escaped with Bonvillian's help when he was
taken from jail to a hospital emergency room, authorities said.
   They apparently were asleep early Saturday in a car parked just
south of Milwaukee when patrolman John Edwards stopped to check the
car. According to police reports, Plummer allegedly drew a gun and
shot Edwards in one hand before speeding away.
   Edwards gave chase but lost them. Their car was found a while
later in a private driveway and police dogs tracked the pair to the
barn.
</TEXT>
