<FIRST>r a AM-CheneyHouseSeat     03-25 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cheney House Seat,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Senator Wins Democratic Nomination for Cheney's Seat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CASPER, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Party officials selected a state
senator Saturday to run for the U.S. House seat left vacant by
newly confirmed Secretary of Defense Dick Cheney.
   Sen. John Vinich defeated opponents Bill Downes, a Casper
attorney, and former state tax commissioner Carrol Orrison to earn
the right to face Republican nominee Craig Thomas, a state
representative in his third term, in the April 26 special election.
   Vinich, who received 49 or the 66 votes cast during the meeting
of the state party's central committee, said the state needs
someone to make its concerns known to the Democrats in Congress.
   ``Rather than being on the outside complaining about the
decisions of the majority party, I will be directly involved and
have the opportunity to speak out on western issues,'' he told
central committee members. ``The majority party has some members
with senseless ideas and no understanding of the West.''
   Cheney, a six-term Republican congressman, gave up the seat less
than two weeks ago when he was confirmed as defense secretary by
the U.S. Senate.
</TEXT>
