<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Greece-Independence     03-25 0119</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Greece-Independence,0122</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greece celebrates fight for independence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greeks on Saturday celebrated the 168th
anniversary of the start of the fight to win independence from the
Turks' Ottoman Empire.
   Premier Andreas Papandreou and President Christos Sartzetakis
attended a Greek Orthodox church service and later joined Cabinet
members, political party leaders and foreign diplomats to watch a
parade of military units and a flyover by Greece's newly purchased
Mirage jet fighters.
   Parades and celebrations were held in towns and cities
throughout Greece.
   The fight for independence began March 25, 1821, when Greek
Orthodox Bishop Germanos raised the blue-and-white Greek flag in
rebellion at the Aghia Lavra monastery in southern Greece. The
nation won independence in 1830.
</TEXT>
