<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOS7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN IAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people, venting their anger over
privileges of the Communist Party elite, rallied Saturday to
support maverick candidate Boris N. Yeltsin on the eve of national
parliamentary elections.
   ``For shame! For shame!'' more than 10,000 people roared when
speakers listed newspapers and politicians who have attacked
Yeltsin for his unorthodox campaign in the Soviet Union's first
contested election in more than 70 years.
   Hundreds of police stood guard nearby.
   Yeltsin is one of thousands of Soviets campaigning nationwide to
win a seat Sunday in the new 2,250-seat Congress of People's
Deputies. The new chamber was created last year in broad electoral
reforms championed by President Mikhail Gorbachev.
   Since his ouster as Moscow's Communist Party boss in 1987,
Yeltsin has emerged as an anti-establishment crusader against
privileges for the powerful, including access to special stores,
better food and chauffeured luxury cars.
   Critics in the party's Central Committee accuse him of accepting
the same privileges.
   Thousands chanted Yeltsin's name at the peaceful rally in a vast
parking lot next to Lenin Stadium, supporting his campaign promise
to work to reduce the privileges if voters elect him.
   ``Do away with special privileges for politicians and
bureaucrats!'' said a placard one demonstrator held aloft on a ski
pole. ``Servants of the people should have to stand in line!'' said
another banner.
   Hundreds of police lined the entrance to the parking lot. Scores
of reinforcements waited in dozens of buses parked nearby. Around a
bend in the road, hidden by trees, 50 military trucks _ packed with
soldiers _ were parked. Rally organizers from three Moscow
political action groups had obtained permission for the three-hour
rally after convincing authorities it would be better than having
an illegal demonstration _ such a March 19 rally in which thousands
of Yeltsin supporters marched through downtown Moscow.
   Yeltsin, 58, is running against 51-year-old Yevgeny Brakov,
director of the ZIL auto factory, for the right to represent all of
Moscow with its 6.5 million registered voters.
   Brakov's campaign has been focused on the issue of ending
chronic Soviet food shortages. ``I am for a speedy decision on the
food problem, development of food and processing industries,'' he
said in an article written for the newspaper Economic Gazette.
   Speakers at the rally also praised the political reforms that
have made Sunday's election possible.
   ``This is the first time in 70 years we have had a real
election,'' speaker Igor Chubais told them.
   He was followed by popular poet Yevgeny Yevtushenko, who was
loudly applauded after reading a short poem praising Gorbachev's
policy of glasnost, or openness, which allowed the rally to take
place.
   A British newspaper on Sunday quoted Yeltsin as saying in an
interview that restructuring should have begun ``with problems
which everyone would have understood,'' including food
distribution, housing and living standards.
   ``We have wasted 3{ years,'' The Sunday Telegraph quoted him as
saying. ``Now the new direction is concentrating on exactly those
three points. We have admitted that we did not have an overall
conception of perestroika (restructuring).''
   Yelstin said he and Gorbachev have different ideas on how to
push through perestroika, but did not see himself as ``an
alternative to Mr. Gorbachev,'' according to the newspaper.
   Yeltsin said the government needs to cut military spending and
chop investment in industrial construction by about 40 percent.
   He also inveighed against privileges for the elite. ``How can
one tolerate one man eating good quality sausage and another not.
Perestroika should have started in the (Communist) party,'' he said.
   Voting takes place Sunday at 180,000 stations, which will open
from 7 a.m. to 8 p.m. in the country's 11 time zones.
   First results are expected late Sunday night, but full results
will not be known for about 10 days, said the official Soviet news
agency Tass. Election officials say than 190 million of the 280
million Soviets are eligible to vote.
   On Sunday, 1,500 seats are being contested, and the other 750
seats were filled by the Communist Party and other officially
sanctioned groups. About 80 percent of the candidates are party
members.
</TEXT>
