<BYLINE>By HELEN J. SIMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST ORANGE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car driven by an elderly man smashed
through a glass window in a crowded supermarket Saturday afternoon,
injuring at least 10 people before it came to a halt at a cash
register counter, authorities said.
   One cashier at the Pathmark supermarket suffered serious back
and internal injuries when she was hit by the car and flying glass
and brick, said West Orange Police Chief Edward M. Palardy.
   ``The operator of the vehicle blacked out at the driver's
wheel,'' Palardy said. ``He proceeded down the parking aisle,
accelerating and nearly striking several people who had to dodge
and dart out of the way. It was mass chaos.''
   Robert Wunderle, spokesman for Pathmark's parent company,
Supermarkets General, said two other cashiers and five customers
also were injured. However, Palardy said the other seven people
injured were all customers. The discrepancy could not immediately
be resolved.
   He said West Orange police would examine the car for mechanical
problems.
   The driver, 80-year-old Wolodymyr Szpyrka of West Orange, his
70-year-old wife Ewhenia, the seriously injured employee and the
seven others were taken to several area hospitals, Palardy said.
   The driver was listed in stable condition at Mountainside
Hospital in Montclair, Palardy said. The nature of his injuries
were not immediately known.
   Mrs. Szpyrka was in shock and not able to say if her husband
blacked out regularly, the police chief said.
   ``Because of his age and the seriousness of the accident, we'll
examine whether he should be allowed to keep his license,'' Palardy
said, adding that the driver was not cited.
   Several hundred people were inside the store in a small shopping
mall in this northern New Jersey community northwest of Newark,
said Robert Wunderle, spokesman for Pathmark's parent company,
Supermarkets General.
   The four-door Buick was about 50 feet from the store when it hit
a dip, flew into the air and crashed through the window, said John
George of East Orange, a witness. The front half of the car was
lodged inside the building for about 1{ hours before being removed
by a tow truck about 5:30 p.m.
   Bobi Bennett of West Orange was standing at a checkout counter
when the car stopped near the register where she waited in line.
   ``He (the driver) was just sitting there staring. I thought he'd
had a heart attack or something and he was gunning the engine for
quite a while,'' Ms. Bennett said. ``Somebody had to scream at him
to turn the car off.''
   Ms. Bennett said she used a bar that separates grocery orders to
help pry out a woman trapped between a register and the car. The
woman was screaming, but most customers remained calm, she said.
   Isakson said no one was trapped under the car, and no mechanical
equipment was needed to remove the injured people.
