<HEAD>City's Plan To Cut Benefits For Retired Police Dogs Draws Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City officials thought they would save
$13,500 annually by pulling retired German Shepherds out of the
public trough, but the action brought a snarling response from the
dogs' human supporters.
   The trouble began when the Police Department decided to cut off
retirement benefits for over-the-hill police dogs, who had been
receiving pensions of food, biscuits and veterinary care.
   First, the Fraternal Order of Police announced plans for a
lawsuit. Then a group of activists gathered more than 1,000
signatures on petitions urging Police Commissioner Willie L.
Williams to reverse the decision.
   The leader of the petition campaign, Randi L. Biba, also wrote
to various dog food manufacturers pleading for help.
   Finally, Alpo Petfood Inc., based in Allentown, came through
this week with an offer to provide free canned or dry food for the
36 retirees until the issue is resolved. Alpo volunteered to give
food to police for distribution.
   But police officials said they're not quite ready to shake on
the deal.
   ``I don't know what our decision will be,'' said police
spokesman Capt. Richard DeLise. ``We're going to have to look at
this closely to see what it's going to entail. We have to figure
out logistics.''
   DeLise said Deputy Police Commissioner Thomas McGeehan would
meet with Alpo officials to talk about the company's proposal.
   ``We're getting out of the retired dog food business,'' DeLise
said.
