<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-89 2358EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FAA-UFOs     03-25 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FAA-UFOs,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Traffic Controllers Report Unidentified Radar Targets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONGMONT, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   False aircraft images on radar screens
startled air traffic controllers at an Federal Aviation
Administration center, but one official said the problem may have
been a computer that ``just went haywire.''
   Controllers at the Denver Air Route Traffic Control Center ``at
several sectors were astonished to see numerous `UFOs' appearing on
their radar displays,'' Kevin Cain, a center spokesman, said of the
incident on Tuesday.
   Cain, the center's National Air Traffic Controllers Association
safety chairman, released written comments on the incident Friday.
   FAA officials would not comment directly on the incident.
   ``These unidentified targets looked like actual aircraft, with
apparently normal speeds and altitudes,'' Cain's statement said.
``Some controllers had a dozen or more of these targets merging
with actual aircraft targets over a half-hour period.''
   Mitch Barker, an FAA spokesman at the regional office in
Seattle, would not directly answer when questioned about the false
targets.
   Cain said he believed the problem was caused by a relatively new
computer system, in operation at the center in September 1987.
   ``The head of the safety committee for the controller's union
believes that the new computer just went haywire for that period of
time,'' Cain said. ``We have not seen anything like this out there
before.''
   Barker said the problems were caused by the data feed from the
Grand Junction radar site.
   ``They were having a problem with the transponders (which
automatically send information from the aircraft to the center),''
said Barker. The FAA would only confirm that the controllers were
not receiving correct data blocks of identifying information that
appear on controller screens.
   ``They had, a day before, a commercial power outage in Grand
Junction. This problem appeared after that outage,'' Barker said.
``A relay had gone bad. They believe that outage had something to
do with it.''
   Barker said the radar feed was only out for 51 minutes and
adjoining radar sites were able to provide sufficient radar data to
the sectors involved.
   Other controllers at the site said it is not unusual to get
false targets on occasion, but such a large number of false targets
might be dangerous. During busy traffic times, one sector might
have about 15 real targets on the screen, although Cain said the
false targets appeared at a slow time of day.
   The center controls aircraft between airports in about 35
sectors, an area including Colorado and Wyoming and parts of Utah,
Oklahoma, Kansas, Nebraska and South Dakota.
   Cain said there have been a number of computer and radio
problems at the center during the last year.
</TEXT>
