<FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-89 2355EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Customs-InternalProbe     03-25 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Customs-Internal Probe,340</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Customs Service has deployed
nationwide a special group of ``field associates'' to investigate
drug-related corruption and other internal problems, an agency
spokesman said Saturday night.
   The spokesman, Richard Weart, said these personnel had been
specially selected ``to be alert for serious types of corruption.''
   ``They are assigned to a district office or regional office or
to the office of enforcement. But they are not directly assigned to
internal affairs,'' Weart said.
   He said they are not paid extra for their role in monitoring
other employees.
   ``But if the situation arises they will report to a local office
of internal affairs on such matters,'' Weart said.
   The Washington Post reported in Sunday's editions that Assistant
Customs Commissioner for Internal Affairs William F. Green had
recruited about 40 agency employees as field associates assigned to
key offices nationwide to ``keep their eyes and ears open for any
wrongdoing'' among their colleagues.
   The Post said the group was selected from among recruits
training at the Federal Law Enforcement Academy at Glynco, Ga.
   Weart acknowledged that the group had received additional
training for uncovering serious types of corruption, such as theft
of cash or other evidence seized by the service. But he said they
were ``certainly not trained as spies.''
   ``In our view, for an agency that is on the front line of drug
interdiction we intend to hold our employees to a higher
standard,'' he said.
   Weart said the approach of having employees act as informers
against their co-workers was ``nothing new,'' explaining that the
code of conduct for federal employees required reporting wrongdoing
by fellow workers.
   He added that the program was modeled after a New York City
police department internal investigation headed by ex-officer Frank
Serpico.
   Recently two Customs inspectors were arrested in Hidalgo, Texas,
on bribery charges and five agency workers were arrested in New
York with airport and Agriculture Departmewnt workers on
drug-dealing charges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
